column117: LULAC is hosting a Cafecito on Saturday, June 25, 2022 at CASA’s Multicultural Center discussing the mental health effects of the COVID-19 pandemic on communities of color as well as the unique mental health needs of the DMV area’s large undocumented, Spanish-speaking, immigrant, and refugee community. The English discussion will run from 10:00 a.m. - 11:00 a.m. EDT, and the Spanish discussion will run from noon-1:00 p.m.  Stick around for a community health fair with health screenings, games, Zumba, snacks, and more!

column59:
Challenges were dealing with fatigue and sickness after three weeks of consistent travel. These were addressed by pushing through it, but planning to spread out our travel in future cycles.

Another challenge was our anti-racism event where the leader of the event did not like the white lens the talk was presented in and therefore stopped the talk. This resulted in an extremely fruitful discussion, but did teach us to be more aware of how we are framing our talks and discussions.

column58: Concerns with - Ethics, Confidentiality, and Securing Data
column60:
People can feel confused, threatened, or annoyed by people with different views and backgrounds. 

It is challenging to understand individuals' different expectations of the various cultures and beliefs the SUNO Team was interacting with.

column2: NRHA / Cycle 4 July 2022 Monthly Report
column55: July marked the beginning of the new cycle for the All of Us Research Program CPGI consortia, including NRHA. Program Services Coordinator Lea Mann submitted the End of Cycle 3 Report on July 15, 2022. Program Services Senior Director Laura Hudson submitted NRHA’s Cycle 4 Statement of Work and corresponding budget on July 22, 2022. The National Rural Health Association would like to extend our deepest thanks to our Engagement Counselor Rachelle Ciulla and our Communications Counselor Rob Bartnichak for their ceaseless support throughout the cycle transition.  Though NRHA, and subsequently our sub-awardees, have not received our Cycle 4 funding, we have been using this time to plan accordingly for the funding year ahead. NRHA has been effectively communicating with our sub-awardees about our reporting & funding status which has made the cycle transition flow with more ease. Moreover, NRHA has received commitment from Maryland Rural Health Association Executive Director Jonathan Dayton that MDRHA will be present at the Cycle 4 DMV Monthly Market Calls, along with NRHA staffer Lea Mann.
column58: No concerns were expressed this month by potential participants.
column59:
It was brought to the attention of NRHA that our sub-awardee Louisiana Rural Health Association (LRHA) did not have the capacity to expend their Cycle 3 budget by the deadline of June 30th. NRHA had previously discussed and planned with LRHA Executive Director Denae Hebert that LRHA’s remaining budget would be allocated to co-branded in-person event set-up items, such as a tablecloth, a vertical banner, and flyers for distribution. 

We communicated this challenge to our Engagement Counselor Rachelle Ciulla, who then spoke internally with Pyxis to find a resolution process. LRHA via NRHA is preparing to submit an official request for Pyxis Partners for LRHA to carry-over the funds from Cycle 3 into the Cycle 4 timeline.
column60: NRHA continues to learn more about existing partners and assets within the CPGI consortia and the Program at large. NRHA looks forward to learning how to leverage and build upon existing partnerships to carry out impactful All of Us engagement & education events across the various intersections of rural identity.
column61: Between June 30, 2022, and July 31, 2022, NRHA has communicated with our engagement counselor, Rachelle Ciulla, weekly. NRHA has worked with sub-awardees to discuss details and timelines for Cycle 4 activities and has had internal discussions about how NRHA can continue to enhance our support of our subawardees.  Internal meetings have also been scheduled to discuss upcoming communication activities within NRHA’s platforms.
column62: The All of Us Research Program is working not only to engage rural populations, but also working to understand them. More specifically, the Program wants to empower all the varieties of rural America to take their personal and their community’s health into their own hands.
column63: On July 11, 2022, NRHA met with Lauren Thomann, the local outreach lead who works on the All of Us Research Program Portfolio for the Department of Veterans Affairs (VA), as NRHA has experience in working on rural health and veteran related activities. In this meeting, NRHA learned that the VA has 15 enrollment sites around the U.S. During this meeting, NRHA and the VA discussed areas of collaborative All of Us programming.  These areas include creating rural veteran focused assets, co-exhibiting at the NRHA’s 2023 Annual Rural Health Conference, and connecting their enrollment sites with NRHA’s All of Us sub-awardees.  NRHA looks forward to discussing further plans to collaborate with the VA.

column2: Black Greek Letter Consortium/  Phi Beta Sigma Summary July 2022
column55:
Phi Beta Sigma Fraternity maintained both telecommunications and virtual meeting contact with the BGLC leadership team and the BGLC peer group throughout the thirty-day period of May 26, 2022 – June 25, 2022, by participating in weekly team calls and the bi-monthly social media All of Us team calls. 

During the month of June 2022, Phi Beta Sigma Fraternity coordinators worked to confirm the HPOs and Blood Banks that we may work with on Phase VII for the All of Us research project.  The scheduled activities in Houston TX (on the campus of Huston-Tillotson University) will be in the month of August 2022. The scheduled activities in Itta Bena MS (on the campus of Mississippi Valley State University) will be in the month of October 2022.  

Phi Beta Sigma Fraternity coordinators worked to confirm HPOs and Blood Banks that we may work with on Phase VII for the All of Us research project activities in the Milwaukee WI area.  That activity will be a collaboration with Holy Redeemer Church of God in Christ, a minority faith-based organization.  The scheduled activities will be January 18 – 19, 2023

column58: •	Coordination with available HPOs in the more rural communities that have been identified

The goal is to get the participants to start the engagement process immediately and to get the retention process started, also.
column60: Phi Beta Sigma Fraternity in confirming that the best retention and follow-up method for the All of Us research project information is to combine the initial face-to-face engagement with the use of the HPOs. column2: THEARI/June Admin Report
column55: Accomplishments experienced by our organization this month included four successful student ambassador activities. Ciauna hosted two activities, both of which were remote presentations via Zoom for the Denver Asian American Pacific Islander Commission and the Asian Pacific Development Center (APDC) Behavioral Health Clinic. Miryam, Mikaela, and Deandra tabled at the North Colorado Medical Center for Banner Health. Annabelle tabled at the University Commons at the University of Denver. Our student ambassadors alone educated 260 individuals about the All of Us Research Program in the last five months. Additionally, we tabled at the National Forum of Nursing Workforce Centers in Las Vegas, NV, educating 36 amount of people about All of Us. Lastly, we hosted a webinar with Banner Health and shared information with participants regarding the foundations of the program as well as what it is like to enroll. It has been a very busy but incredibly rewarding last month of our cycle!
column57: We are concerned about continued student engagement and have other students interested in becoming ambassadors for the All of Us Research Program. We find this to be a barrier to participation and would love to pass along our Student Ambassador Program to another community partner to ensure young professionals and students are engaged and promoting this valuable program. Abigail plans to share the Student Ambassador Program packet with Julia before her last day at THEARI so that another community partner could potentially use it in the future.
column59: Challenges experienced by our organization included low participation and engagement with the co-hosted webinar with Banner Health. We did not begin marketing soon enough (3 weeks in advance) and did not consider other calendar factors (Banner Health had a very large webinar the week prior).
column60: Lessons learned from this is that we need to start marketing much sooner, compare calendars in closer detail, and also have a theme to our webinar experience to draw more people. We also recognize Zoom fatigue and need to consider the time of year as well as summer is a challenging season for engagement.
column61: This month's activities included check-ins with each of our student ambassadors, attendance at the Denver Market meeting, we hosted our last internal THEARI team meeting, met with Banner Health to prepare for our co-hosted webinar, four student ambassador activities including two tabling activities and two remote presentations, tabling at the National Forum of Nursing Workforce Centers Conference in Las Vegas, hosted a Zoom celebration for our student ambassadors, co-hosted a webinar with Banner Health, bi-monthly check-ins with Lin, and attended my 1:1 check-in with Julia.
column62:
The best resonating messages this month come from our Student Ambassador Program (SAP) survey. These are direct quotes but responses were anonymous.

"Presenting and pitching the program when we tabled for events certainly allowed me to practice my presentation skills. It challenged me to talk about research in a concise yet comprehensive way. It is definitely a valuable skill that I will continue to hone in future opportunities."

"Becoming a student ambassador was a wonderful and valuable opportunity! It aligned with my interests in health equity. I also couldn't have asked for better support from THEARI and Abigail."

"I think tabling at the hospital was a great activity because that is where we saw the most interest in the program and interacted with the most amount of people. It was a great opportunity to have people learn about the program and then go directly upstairs to enroll or turn in info cards."

"This was a great opportunity to learn more about the program, spread knowledge about the program, and interact with the community to help make people become more involved in the future of medicine."

column2: THEARI/April Admin Report
column55: Accomplishments experienced by our organization this month include two successful student ambassador activities, one was a presentation hosted by Ciauna at RVU for the Colorado Council of Medical Librarians on April 8th, and the other was hosted by Miryam, Mikaela, and Deandra and was a collaboration tabling activity at the North Colorado Medical Center (Banner Health Greeley location). We hosted an Enrollment Information Session for our student ambassadors and THEARI All of Us staff on April 19th with Banner Health. This session better informed us as to how formal enrollment works at an HPO. THEARI was also a part of the NAO Student Panel on April 20th in which Ciauna represented THEARI and shared with over 50 attendees her experience as a student ambassador. We featured all five of our student ambassadors in the April newsletter. We submitted a successful Engagement Strategy as well.
column57: We have not identified any barriers to participation, in fact, we have seen an increase in participation. We believe we have been able to increase our promotion and education for the All of Us Research Program through our student ambassadors' activities and also offering hybrid attendance options when possible for activities.
column59: Challenges experienced this month relate to enrollment. We have spent the last month or more trying to better understand the enrollment process in the Denver Market and have finally reached a point in which we feel like we know how to approach this topic! We appreciate the support from Julia and Gabi in trying to navigate the appropriate enrollment pathways and what is allowable for internal and external use. Our THEARI All of Us team is much more confident in providing the foundational knowledge about enrollment to interested participants in All of Us and we feel we have the right tools to point people in the right direction.
column60: An important lesson learned this month is that we don't have all the answers as a CPGI partner, nor should we. In an attempt to make clearer the enrollment pathways, we have realized that while we are the first line of communication for many interested individuals in All of Us, we don't need to have all the answers. It has become incredibly clear that we need  definite calls to action in our potential FY23 cycle so we can better meet our internal goals and respect the educational reach we have.
column61: This month's activities included two student ambassador activities, Spring Engagement Meeting preparations with Texas Waco AHEC, check-ins with student ambassadors, Journey Bus meeting with Montage, AHEC Community Meeting, internal THEARI team meeting, Denver Market meeting, meeting with Banner Health, Enrollment Information Session with Banner Health for student ambassadors and THEARI All of Us staff, NAO Student Panel, meeting with YMCA of Metro Denver, two, 1:1 check-ins with Julia, and ongoing marketing with a monthly newsletter and social media posts (reports provided separately).
column62: Best resonating messages came out of Ciauna's activity on April 8th. Her audience had great questions about the All of Us Research Program, including: Is there data available for the Native American population? How rigorous is the genomic testing in All of Us? Who controls the data from fitness devices? Does the participant submit the data to NIH, or does it get sent from the company (e.g. Apple) to NIH? These questions have been addressed by Pyxis Partners and highlight the importance of us as a CPGI partner being able to admit when we do not have the answers but seek them out for interested participants in the program.

column2: AAPA / July 2022 Monthly Summary Report
column55:
Our focus this month was on completing and submitting our SOW and budget documents for the 2022-23 program cycle, as well as kicking off initial activities. Tactics/accomplishments included:
- Shared SOW/budget with engagement counselor and communications counselor (7/1).
- Participated in follow-up discussion with engagement counselor and communications counselor to discuss comms tactics (7/13).
- Submitted SOW/budget via online form (7/14).
- Monthly social media posts on AAPA and/or PA Foundation channels - created/published 2 posts - 7/12, 7/22. Topic: BIPOC Mental Health Month. Utilized copy/images from engagement hub/asset portal.
- AoU mention in blog post focused on DEI partnership initiatives - published 7/26. Incorporated description of AoU, its value to PAs, and link to AoU website.
column57: None.
column58: None.
column59: Challenges included coordinating with partner organizations to schedule upcoming meetings for partnership/activity activation. We will continue to communicate with them to find a time that works for all parties to meet in order to get our collaborative initiatives off the ground.
column60: We continue to see new opportunities to weave All of Us messaging into our existing activities and channels. For example, when developing this month's blog post, we saw an opportunity to reference the program and highlight its value to PAs in light of its relevance to the post theme of DEI efforts/partnerships. This blog post was not originally slated as a SOW tactic (we have a separate tactic to develop a separate blog post focused entirely on the program later in the cycle), but we identified a connection point and leveraged the opportunity to promote the program in a small but direct way. We will continue to be on the lookout for ways to integrate the program into our ongoing channels/strategies/assets.
column62: This month's messaging focused on BIPOC/Minority Mental Health Month. We incorporated language in social media posts pointing to the ways in which discrimination and inequalities disproportionately affect the mental health of minority communities. This seemed to resonate well with our audience.

column2: AAPA / June 2022 Monthly Summary Report
column55:
We completed the final activities slated in our 2021-22 SOW this month.
- Communications/social media: Monthly social media posts on AAPA/PA Foundation channels - 6/2, 6/9, 6/14. Incorporated messaging related to Pride Month, Men's Health Week; used social media toolkits provided on Engagement Hub. Communications team developed final quarterly communications article related to All of Us; topic: "Top 10 reasons PAs should consider genetics in their practice." Shared draft with communications counselor for review/editing. Published on News Central section of AAPA website on 6/28.
- CME sessions (AoU conference session, research session, and Genetics & Genomics CME bundle): Enduring sessions on AAPA Learning Central; continuing to collect/compile participation metrics on a monthly basis. 
- Website landing pages: Continuing to collect monthly metrics.
- Follow-up metric from AAPA 2022 Conference - Almost 1 in 5 participants in a post-conference survey reported they noticed NIH All of Us Research Program as a sponsor at AAPA 2022.

In addition to closing out 2021-22 activities, we focused on preparing for the 2022-23 program cycle. We held several internal meetings (see governance activities below) related to developing our SOW activities and budget. We have drafted our SOW activities and budget and are now working on inputting them into the approved SOW/budget templates (received 6/17).
column59: Challenges this month had to do with developing and refining our 2022-23 SOW activities in order to best reflect the needs, priorities, and incentives of our audience. Based on conversations with collaborating partners, we took action to revise our initial ideas and reshape them to better align with our partners' capacity/motivations and audience priorities/incentives.
column60: We continue to see the importance of adapting and modifying plans as needed based on evolving conversations with our partners and insights on our audience and their needs/priorities. For example, in planning conversations with one partner, we learned that our initial plan to target PA faculty members for presentations/demos on the All of Us Research Hub would likely not be as effective or valuable as targeting PA programs and students. Based on this, we have adjusted our proposed strategy/activities to include an activity focused on this specific audience (virtual presentation series to PA programs).

column2: THEARI/May Admin Report
column55: Accomplishments experienced by our organization this month included successful tabling at the Denver Colfax Marathon; nearly 400 people visited our THEARI booth and learned about the All of Us Research Program. We had several student ambassadors activities events this month as well. Ciauna tabled with Banner Health at the Mile High Flea Market with 52 visitors to our THEARI table and Deandra presented to the Osteopathic Medical Student Coalition in a hybrid fashion with 10 in attendance. Mikaela presented to the administration/faculty at Stuart Middle School and Miryam hosted an All of Us social with her fellow medical students at Rocky Vista University (RVU). THEARI hosted a virtual booth with Texas Waco AHEC at the Spring Engagement Meeting and due to the number of visitors to our booth, we were a top 5 exhibit.
column57:
Our current student ambassadors have been asking if THEARI will host student ambassadors again. This is a barrier to participation because THEARI will be unable to serve as the host for future All of Us student ambassadors but believes in the power of student engagement in this program. Finding an organization that would take on our SAP would benefit not only said organization, but the All of Us Research Program and the students as well.

Additional barriers to participation exist with our newly established partnership with Banner Health. We'd like to find another community partner that is interested in working closely with Banner Health.

Abigail will take the initiative and connect with organizations that we believe are potential good fits for some of our program components. Guidance on what we are allowed to share with other community partners would be appreciated as we care about our programs and want to re-home them if possible.
column60: Pyxis Partners has connections with many resources and was able to support THEARI with interns and opportunities. They are interested in continuing to develop partnerships in the future with recommended organizations.
column61: This month's activities included attendance at the Spring Engagement Meeting, student ambassador check-ins, attendance at the AHEC/THEARI group meeting, attendance at the Denver Market meeting, hosted an internal All of Us THEARI team meeting, THEARI staff and student ambassadors along with Banner Health staff tabled at the Denver Colfax Marathon, Deandra presented to the Osteopathic Medical Student Coalition at RVU in a hybrid format, Ciauna tabled with Banner Health staff at the Mile High Flea Market, Mikaela hosted a presentation with the administration/faculty at Stuart Middle School, Miryam hosted a presentation with RVU medical students, attendance at CPGI day, and 1:1 check-in with Julia. Due to so many student ambassadors events this month, a significant amount of time was dedicated to supporting our students and ensuring they had exactly what they needed to be successful.
column62:
One of the best resonating messages include the kudos provided by Julia during the monthly 1:1 check-in. Lin shared this with the THEARI team, highlighting Abigail's dedication to the All of Us Research Program.

Additional positive messaging came from THEARI Board of Directors and staff as well as Banner Health staff that tabled at the Denver Colfax Marathon:

"The event was definitely a success, and we reached out to many people! Dr. Michael Bradfield & Kaylee Hambek from Banner Health were absolutely fantastic and very experienced. Kaylee was in front of the booth, engaging people coming by, and many people trusted in Dr. Bradfield since he was a physician providing insight into personalized medicine."

"Our table was positioned between several other pretty high profile tables, making it easy to chat with people, and I was impressed by how many people where genuinely interested once they started hearing about the AoU opportunity."

column2: ACCESS Monthly Summary Report (June 2022)
column55: Our organization successfully shared an op-ed written by one of our program coordinators this month. This finalized op-ed elaborates more on topics such Asian American health experiences, social media, as well as the power of data collection within the program. We look forward to seeing this work published. Our subawardee, Friends of Parkside, have scheduled a health fair for August. We are excited to plan and table at this event in the upcoming future.
column57: ACCESS was preparing to participate in the NAT Photoshoot with Wondros. We submitted the necessary forms and outlined internally how we wanted to best showcase the Arab American community. The turnaround time for the photoshoot however was very quick. We were sent the run of shows only days before the event, with little time to see if we were selected. Given ACCESS was not selected this year, we hope to prioritize our participation next year to adequately represent the Arab American community we serve.
column58: Main concerns for June were how to best forecast a Scope of Work that would strengthen our engagement objectives. We want to effectively plan and prepare for a variety of educational and recruitment activities that keep our audiences interested. In addition to work with subawardee the Public Health Society at the University of Michigan, we hope to re-initiate collaborative efforts with the Friends of Parkside group.
column59: There were few challenges this month. In regards to participation with our HPO, Henry Ford Health, our primary contact Janine Al-Khafaji has left her position. We are currently working alongside the Henry Ford All of Us Team to facilitate a transition to a new primary point of contact. We will remain connected with Henry Ford Health as we navigate scheduling events for the year to come.
column60: Lessons learned included finalizing and determining what ACCESS’ main goals were for the upcoming year. We begin to navigate the lower tail of the pandemic, as participants are beginning to reach and meet in person more. There is continued respect and sensitivity for the communities we serve in our June planning period.
column61: NAT Photoshoot. CPGI Biweekly Webinar. Biweekly Meetings with program officers.
column62: June was a month focused on outlining and preparing for the upcoming programmatic year. ACCESS submitted a draft Scope of Work, highlighting key events we aim to execute for the year. We are currently strategizing to start our 4th year participating in this program off with a strong start. Reflecting on past successes and strategies has allowed us to cater our approach to best fit our community. June allowed opportunity for development of a sustainable, growth-focused agenda.

column2: UnidosUS Monthly Summary Report (April 2022)
column55:
UnidosUS and its subgrantees continued to share information about the All of Us Research Program on social media with one paid post by UnidosUS on Facebook and Instagram reaching more than 63,000 through April 24th. Reach of this post is expected to increase as it is continuing to run through April 30th.

LAMDA assisted with registering 35 individuals by hosting an event in collaboration with two HPOs—Northwestern University (NU) and University of Chicago Illinois (UCI). NU registered 12 individuals and UCI registered 23 individuals. While there was a logistical challenge that required participants to enter the LAMDA office to receive educational materials versus them being provided at the All of Us van brought by UCI, this was still a successful event.

column55: During the month of June we were successful in launching our Science is Fun - Pinky Promise videos, showcasing to science teachers that we worked with during this cycle to introduce the All of Us Research Program to their high school students.  We challenged them to be creative to make science fun and I know we were successful by the videos posted.  We also hosted a booth during the Let The Good TImes Roll Festival during the Juneteenth weekend where we brought visibility and awareness to the AoU program.  We were allowed on the main stage to talk about the AoU program twice and we walked through the crowd with QR codes and encouraged participation.  The Mayor for the City of Shreveport was there, we took pictures, as well as, made sure he was signed up for the program as well.  We believe the turn out and awareness was very beneficial to our efforts.

column2: LULAC Monthly Summary Report (June 2022)
column8: League of United Latin American Citizens (LULAC)National Office
column55:
LULAC participated in weekly check-in calls with our engagement counselor, Rima Matsumoto and communications counselor Samantha Santoro as LULAC planned, coordinated and implemented the upcoming in-person cafecito on June 25th regarding mental health. LULAC also met with NHCOA, NHMA, Mary’s Center and CASA to discuss the cafecito event and the health fair component to the event. LULAC shared an invitation and more information about this event at the DMV market call on June 21, 2022. 
On June 25th, LULAC held a successful event at CASA in Hyattsville, MD in collaboration with NHCOA, NHMA, Mary’s Center and CASA. All co-hosting organizations had a table with health related resources for the community. We also had an AoU table where all organizations volunteered along with Pyxis team members to engage and address questions about the program. We had giveaways and a tabletop display along with other program materials that were also displayed at the organization’s tables. At the AoU booth, there were 21 engagements. Mary’s Center brought their enrollment privacy booth to help facilitate enrollment to those community members interested in participating in the program, and successfully helped enroll 10 participants. NHCOA transported 10 older adults to the event to participate in the Spanish session of the mental health cafecito. Mary’s Center was also able to bring a behavioral provider specialist to speak to community members about the services they provide around mental health.
column58: not enough mental health resources available in Spanish and for senior citizens.
column59: Given all CPGI organizations are finalizing activities and reports for this cycle, and in addition, LULAC is in the middle of planning and coordinating our largest annual event scheduled for the end of July, which will also be our first one back in-person, we found ourselves in a crunch time for the June 25 event. It took time and good effort to bring together all co-hosting organizations, as well as the additional local organizations providing health tests and screenings. In hindsight, we could have done a better job with communications and more time to execute, but this experience has provided us with lessons learned for future collaborations in the DMV and other markets.
column60: During the month of June, LULAC learned that for future collaborative events, we should have more meetings among co-hosting organizations leading up to the event so everyone is better informed of logistics and assignments, in order to avoid making last minute decisions. Although we understand that the last minute changes were due to unexpected illness with team members and vendors, as well as competing events on the same day by our organization where we had no previous knowledge. Also, to include additional time and efforts on promotion including canvassing in surrounding areas to increase community participation.
column61:
During the month of June, LULAC met with Rima and Samantha to finalize the logistics for the Mental Health Cafecito. Samantha helped put together a social media plan and talking points for the event. In addition, Rima was instrumental in building the connection with CASA de Maryland. She helped us acquire the space and build partnerships with NHCOA, NHMA and Mary’s Center. We also held prep call with NHCOA, NHMA, Mary’s Center and CASA de Maryland to discuss the cafecito event and the overall  health fair component to the event. LULAC also participated in the DMV market call and shared an invitation and more information about this event on June 21, 2022. 
On June 14th, LULAC attended the CPGI Biweekly Meeting and learned about the new markets and additional information  for cycle 4. Unfortunately, LULAC was unable to attend the NY Market call as we had a previously scheduled all staff planning meeting for  our upcoming National Convention. 
Lastly this month, Rima and the LULAC team have been discussing the execution plan for the 2022 LULAC National Convention that is taking place in San Juan, PR in late July.  We have discussed outreach and exhibiting and speaking opportunities.  We also provided responses to the review committee of our Strategic Plan and are in the process of developing our SOW for the next funding cycle.
column63: Families joined us for healthy snacks, games and health screenings. We were able to secure free HIV testing through La Clinica del Pueblo, and Breast Care for Washington DC’s mammography van providing free breast cancer screenings, as well as COVID-19 response materials through CASA.

column2: LULAC Monthly Summary Report (July 2022)
column55:
During the month of July, LULAC participated in weekly check-in calls with our engagement counselor, Rima and communications counselor Samantha. In addition, LULAC was introduced to our new engagement counselor, Mae Sandberg. 
Throughout the month LULAC worked closely with Rima to develop a cohesive and well thought out scope of work for 2022-2023. LULAC ended with excess potential activities and had to make minor edits to our original plan because we did not want to overextend ourselves and our capacity for the year. We structured our workplan to be intentional and provide results to meet our 5 year plan that aligns with the program.
In addition to this LULAC has been working extensively on finalizing pending items for our National Convention in Puerto Rico. Our convention will take place from July 25- July 30, 2022 in San Juan, PR. Our local Puerto Rican council will be manning the AoU Research Program booth from Wednesday, July 27- 29. The council has been trained to discuss the program and direct people to the JoinAllofUs.org/GO webpage for more information about the program. In addition, our council will be able to facilitate any surveys of people who are interested in participating. They will also be distributing information trifold in English and Spanish flyers during our expo hall. There is a Spanish All of Us Research Program ad printed in our program book for the convention with a call to visit the JoinAllofUs.org/GO webpage and number to call for more information.
column59: During this month LULAC did not experience any challenges. Rima Matsumoto and Samantha Santoro have been incredibly helpful. We appreciate Rima’s assistance throughout the drafting of the scope of work and budget plan and her attention to detail. This made the process a lot smoother.
column60: During this month LULAC’s Health Programs Coordinator learned how to develop a scope of work for the year that is both intentional and cohesive. When she was on board last year in June the scope of work and budget had already been submitted and in the review process.
column61:
During the month of July LULAC worked closely with our engagement counselor, Rima Matsumoto, to develop a scope of work for cycle 4. LULAC is proud of the plan we have developed throughout the year. We knew that we wanted to have multiple touch points for participants and more events that are bilingual. The strategy we have put together aligns with the program’s five year goal of increasing enrollment in the program. A previous goal of the program was to increase awareness and provide insight into the mission of the program. This meant hosting general events to explain and provide an introduction to the program. LULAC wants to continue introducing the program to our growing membership base and with time expand to additional markets that we service and align with programming. However, we now want to have a more direct and clear call to action of enrolling. 
Lastly this month, Rima and the LULAC team have been discussing the execution plan for the 2022 LULAC National Convention that is taking place in San Juan, PR in late July.  We have discussed outreach, exhibiting and speaking opportunities.  We also submitted our budget and scope of work for this upcoming cycle 2022-2023.

column2: NRHA / Cycle 3 June 2022 Monthly Summary Report
column55: NRHA’s “Rural Research Influencer” Dr. Kevin Bennett, University of South Carolina, had the opportunity to meet with the Data Research Center (DRC). This meeting arose from a Spring Engagement Meeting panel Dr. Bennet participated.  The DRC invited Dr. Bennett, via our Engagement Counselor Rachelle Ciulla, to give feedback on the lack of an option to stratify All of Us data for rural areas, as he spoke about in the panel. Dr. Bennett offered the idea of creating a rural variable, rather than using zip codes, for privacy reasons; he also discussed how beneficial it would be for community groups to be able to access the AoU data in summary form; it would give them more information about their communities. The summary (and deidentified) data could be used for funding opportunities, community needs assessments or more. The Program’s data could be used for improving community health beyond its use by data scientists.  Dr. Bennett will speak more with the DRC, along with his colleague Dr. Samuel Baxter of Clemson University to discuss institutions and their data user agreements. NRHA members learned about the Workbench and looked to establish a data user agreement for their university so they could access the data, they found one existed already, but they have never heard about. It seems like even the existence of the AoU data user agreement can be siloed among universities.
column57: NRHA appreciates the DRC’s invitation to Dr. Bennett to discuss barriers to both rural participation in the Program and the Workbench.  We look forward to continuing to discuss these barriers and potential solutions in Cycle 4.
column58:
This month being June, our sub-awardee, the Louisiana Rural Health Association, shared the Pride Month content that the Program provided. LRHA Executive Director Denae Hebert shared this about the engagement with the content:  

“I wanted to note that we had more engagement on June’s posts than any other month.  However, not all of the engagement was positive.  The majority of the comments we received were anti-LGBTQ+ (since the posts were related to Pride Month).  None of them rose to the level of hate comments so I did not delete or respond to them.  They were generally along the lines of “being gay is a mental illness/sin” and similar comments.  Some comments were rebuttals to these comments.  I will still count all engagement regardless of the type in the reporting but just wanted to share for your information.” 

If the Program has any specific drafted responses that we should provide to our subawardees or if they would like to discuss the LRHA’s experience with Ms. Herbert, we are happy to help in anyway possible. Or perhaps in Cycle 4, NRHA can discuss potential responses with our communications team lead that we can share with our subawardees.
column59:
NRHA subawardees were slow to provide their social media metrics. While NRHA staffer Lea Mann has created submission forms for our subawardees to provider their social media data, NNRHA plans to continue enhancing our reporting system for our subawardees and partners in Cycle 4. 

NRHA’s sub-awardee the Louisiana Rural Health Association (LRHA) had an All of Us related post denied by Facebook when trying to post the content. Facebook provided the following explanation for its rejection of the post, “it doesn’t comply with our Ads About Social Issues, Elections or Politics policy.” The post content included a Pride Month video asset along with the caption, “Black gay men are the only population in which new HIV cases have been growing since 2001. The @AllofUsResearch Program aims to help reduce health disparities like this by making sure there is real representation in health research. When there is actual diversity, researchers can learn more about our differences. This #Pride2022, you can help too if you sign up and #JoinAllofUs at JoinAllofUs.org/Together.”  LRHA resolved to not post the content but did inform NRHA of the issue they ran into so we may make the Program aware of this hurdle.
column60:
NRHA continues to learn more about existing assets in the asset portal that can be used by our subawardees in numerous ways. It was great to be able to provide several flyers in both English and Spanish for the Arizona Rural Health Conference through the AzRHA’s exhibit space.  

Another lesson learned was that even though the Program, and NRHA, have been educating our stakeholders for years, there is still opportunity to reach those who have either not been informed or those who do not have complete information about the Program. We look forward to continuing, modifying, and expanding our engagement efforts in Cycle 4.
column61: Between May 31, 2022, and June 30, 2022, NRHA has communicated with our engagement counselor, Rachelle Ciulla, weekly. NRHA has worked with sub-awardees on activities and had internal discussions about sub-awardee priorities related to the project including considering additional target markets for the next cycle proposal. Internal meetings have also been discussed regarding upcoming communication activities.  NRHA staff were able to attend all Target Market meetings. Regarding information disseminations and CPGI governance activities, NRHA staff member Lea Mann has been able to represent NRHA at the target market meetings, webinars, and sub-awardee meetings. NRHA promoted the All of Us observances of Pride Month, Men’s Health Week, and World Sickle Cell Day social media toolkits through our platforms.
column62:
Working with trusted community partners like providers, potentially other health professional preceptors, or other groups already located within the community is a wonderful way to encourage engagement and enrollment.  

Donating your data to the program is like donating to your community, the research gets closer to home, impacting health outcomes in your community. If not, those in power are making health decisions about you without you.
column63:
At the end of June, NRHA received an outline on an All of Us-centric Community Health Worker (CHW) Training by Janel Lowman, a certified community health worker trainer. NRHA contracted with Ms. Lowman earlier in the cycle to develop this outline, as NRHA believes that CHWs can be a key resource in engaging and educating rural populations about the All of Us Research Program. NRHA has since reviewed and made comments on this outline and has also sent it to our engagement and communication counselors for their review and comment. NRHA has invited Janel Lowman to our weekly meeting with our counselors from Pyxis to discuss her work and what action we will be taking in Cycle 4 to move this project forward.  

Through the Engagement Incubator, NRHA staffer Laura Hudson connected with Daniel Moretti of Standford PrideNet. Daniel, Laura, and Lea met on June 1st and discussed several ways to collaborate especially in the new Target Market of California. In Cycle 4, we discussed PrideNet serving as a speaker on the podcast for the California State Rural Health Association to discuss AoU. We also discussed connecting their regional coordinators with our subawardees and other state rural health associations. There may also be interest in working together on either a virtual “fireside chat” or perhaps rural specific materials for their target population. NRHA is excited about this new collaboration in Cycle 4 made possible, in part, by the Program.
column155: NRHA’s “Rural Research Influencer” Dr. Kevin Bennett, University of South Carolina, had the opportunity to meet with the Data Research Center (DRC). This meeting arose from a Spring Engagement Meeting panel Dr. Bennet participated.  The DRC invited Dr. Bennett, via our Engagement Counselor Rachelle Ciulla, to give feedback on the lack of an option to stratify All of Us data for rural areas, as he spoke about in the panel. Dr. Bennett offered the idea of creating a rural variable, rather than using zip codes, for privacy reasons; he also discussed how beneficial it would be for community groups to be able to access the AoU data in summary form; it would give them more information about their communities. The summary (and deidentified) data could be used for funding opportunities, community needs assessments or more. The Program’s data could be used for improving community health beyond its use by data scientists.  Dr. Bennett will speak more with the DRC, along with his colleague Dr. Samuel Baxter of Clemson University to discuss institutions and their data user agreements. NRHA members learned about the Workbench and looked to establish a data user agreement for their university so they could access the data, they found one existed already, but they have never heard about. It seems like even the existence of the AoU data user agreement can be siloed among universities.

column2: JSMW Monthly Summary Report (March 2022)
column55:
In March 2022, JSMW had performed following activities: 
- Revised the JSMW-All of Us Landing Webpage on the jsmw.org per the program feedback and officially published. 
- Sent social media promotional message on Facebook including announcing the published Landing page. The Facebook group has ~600 contacts. The post was shared by 1 user. 
- Sent social media promotional message on WhatsApp groups including announcing the published Landing page. We have about ~900 contacts across 5 Whatsapp Groups. 
- JSMW had sent the monthly update to JSMW members via Email. This email also included the announcement regarding the new JSMW-All of Us Landing webpage on jsmw.org. The email is sent to ~900 contacts.
https://jainsocietydc.bmetrack.com/c/v?e=1415C90&c=B6095&t=0&l=6E4DDFA8&email=ZtV3Y64k6xJnBRMLQ7cgpXzBjzlZ2TJR
- Started planning for Mahavir Janma Kalyanak (MJK) on May 1st, 2022. We've decided to talk about All of Us Research Program during the announcements part of the event program. We expect to have an attendance of ~700+ members on this in-person event. We are also working on possibilities to showcase an All of Us info table during the event.
- JSMW has started working on forms/paperwork for the contract renewal of the next funding cycle and discussed the activities/goals on March 28th.
- Working with a JSMW Sub-committee to sponsor a month-long Health Event "Step Challenge" targeted for May. 
- JSMW had visited the MEA Bus in early March and exchanged ideas and possibilities to have such setup made in the JAINA convention in July 2023. 
- JSMW have published an article summarizing the February's Heart Event and an advertisement. This newsletter is published on JSMW.org and mailed to households.

column2: HACU Monthly Summary Report (April 2022)
column55: On April 4th and 5th, HACU hosted the 37th Annual National Capitol Forum, virtually. The All of Us program was featured in the presentation of the Opening Plenary of the event and also included an All of Us ad in the conference program and promotions. Over 260 representatives from across the United States attended the Capitol Forum.  HACU also signed an addendum with Pyxis for an additional activity for this cycle to convene HSI community colleges in June for an informative session in collaboration with the Pyxis team. This month, we met with Kim Cantor to discuss the activity and began brainstorming, planning and coordinating the convening of HSI Community Colleges that will serve as a virtual roundtable discussion to education higher education institutions about the All of Us program and how to obtain DURA's with the program. HACU is currently gathering a list of institutions and will begin reaching out to campuses in May for the convening to occur in June. In the month of April, HACU also met with our engagement counselor for our biweekly check-in calls. We also connected with our communications counselor at one of the biweekly meetings to discuss communication needs, updates and progress.
column61: The HACU team conducted several internal meetings to discuss the strategy for the next All of Us cycle.  The team collectively worked on the strategy proposal and submitted it. We also met to discuss the additional opportunity to convene  HSI community colleges and are beginning to identify institutions to invite for this event. We also informed our counselors of staff changes at HACU and connect the interim comms person to our comms counselor to ensure access to asset portal and other platforms.

column2: ACCESS July 2022 Monthly Recap
column55: We have ordered our branded and co-branded AoU materials in collaboration with Henry Ford Health System. We have also recruited a new subawardee to join the important work we're doing in the Detroit market for our next funding cycle.
column61:
This month we focused on finalizing our Y4 scope of work for the All of Us Research Program. Our team is excited and grateful to be uplifting the program and recruiting participants from our community.  Our strategy to engage our community includes: 
1. Working in close partnership with our HPO to reach community members where they’re at. As a program enrollment site, Henry Ford Health is able to assist us with program goals, participants enrollment, and retention
2. Working with local universities to engage and educate professes and students about the All of Us research program 
3. Working with smaller community organizations and faith-based organizations to help bridge the gap of participant engagement and education 
4. Co-branding All of Us related materials with the ACCESS, Henry Ford Health and Public Health Society logos 
5. Multiple touchpoint of of engagement and education to build trust with the community 
6. Continuing to utilize Arabic translated FAQ sheets at outreach events to remove any language barriers when one is interested in learning about the program
7. Testing different platforms to raise awareness about the program. An example of this would be the All of Us Scavenger Hunt posted on the University of Michigans website where students can learn about the research program through an interactive game created by the All of Us team members

column2: NRHA / Cycle 3 May 2022 Monthly Report
column55:
May was jampacked with programming for NRHA and its sub-awardees when talking about the All of Us Research Program. Regarding information disseminations and CPGI governance activities, NRHA staff member Lea Mann has been able to represent NRHA at the Spring Engagement Meeting, Annual CPGI Meeting, target market meetings, webinars, and sub-awardee meetings. NRHA promoted the All of Us AAPI Heritage Month, Mental Health Awareness Month, National Arab American Heritage Month, and Older Americans Month social media toolkits through our platforms. NRHA also discussed a potential paid co-branded Facebook opportunity with our engagement counselor.  

Most notably, on Thursday, May 12, 2022, NRHA hosted AoU Chief Engagement Officer Dr. Karriem Watson in-person at our Annual Rural Health Conference in Albuquerque, New Mexico as the Terry Reilly Keynote Speaker. Dr. Watson presented an information session titled, “The All of Us Research Program: Engaging Rural Communities to Achieve Health Equity.” Dr. Watson successfully engaged an audience of around 200 rural health professionals with his personal journey in precision medicine research and with facts and figures on the All of Us Research Program. The audience was curious to know how the Program can and will do more to engage rural populations. Dr. Watson was able to have honest, reflective answers for the audience on how he sees the program can do more to engage rural populations in the Program. After Dr. Watson’s presentations, NRHA and TX AHEC East Waco Region waited outside the lecture hall with signs that directed the audience to engage with us if they had further questions about the Program.  

As mentioned in previous reports, at NRHA’s Annual Conference, NRHA co-hosted an All of Us Research Program exhibit with TX AHEC East, Waco Region. The Conference boasted a healthy attendance of 843 people. Ashley Bearden and Micah Bolden of TX AHEC East, Waco Region traveled to NM to staff the All of Us booth, along with NRHA staff Laura Hudson and Lea Mann. Our Engagement Counselor Rachelle Ciulla also staffed this exhibit while also assisting Dr. Watson on-site, as needed.  NRHA ordered all the Program promotional materials, as well as general exhibit assets, including a table runner & a vertical banner, needed for the conference. Texas AHEC East- Waco provided the printed materials. Also, Ms. Ciulla met with the state rural health association leaders briefly during their convening within the NRHA conference.  

In May, NRHA coordinated with our Engagement Counselor Rachelle Ciulla and our “Rural Research Influencer” Dr. Kevin Bennett to have Dr. Bennet participate in a panel on May 4, 2022, during the 2022 Spring Engagement Meeting. The panel was titled, “Building a diverse All of Us Researcher Community: Highlights of impactful engagement activities.” In this panel, Program researchers shared their impactful strategies and activities that can be used to inform future work by additional program partners. Dr. Bennett specifically spoke about the barriers when conducting rural health research on the All of Us research workbench. Dr. Bennett expressed the following barriers to conducting precision medicine research in rural populations: availability of data and equitable data; by this Dr. Bennett expanded to say that the datasets never cover all aspects of rural, as smaller areas get lost in the shuffle in larger counties that are urban. Moreover, participation from rural populations is missing because of lack of transportation or time to go to large care centers, and when they do get to the large health centers, it’s hard to talk to people because they are dealing with a myriad of other health issues. Lastly, it is hard for rural community leaders to navigate the data because they are not part of a larger university or organization that can provide support as they engage in the workbench. From this panel, we have seen positive feedback, as our Engagement Counselor Rachelle Ciulla reached out to Dr. Bennett after his panel to ask him to join a conversation with the Data Research Center (DRC), as DRC had brought up the lack of an option to stratify data for rural areas.  Our Engagement Counselor is currently coordinating with Dr. Bennett to set up a meeting between him and the DRC to discuss this lack of an option among other concerns of rural researchers on the All of Us workbench. 

This month, NRHA met with its sub-awardee the Louisiana Rural Health Association to discuss their strategy & budget for the remainder of Cycle 3. NRHA’s engagement counselor was able to join the call and have a very productive conversation with LRHA Executive Director Denae Hebert on allocating remaining funds to in-person event assets, such as a vertical banner, tablecloth, table signs, etc. LRHA plans to further connect with our Communications Counselor Rob Bartnichak about LRHA branded asset creation.  LRHA also shared the All of Us social media observances in May; those social media engagements have been entered into Network Ninja.  

In Arizona, this month, NRHA met with AZ Rural Health Association leadership to discuss their activities as collaborators for the remainder of Cycle 3 and their interest in participating in NRHA’s Cycle 4 programming with All of Us as sub-awardees and participants in the developing Arizona Target Market. From this conversation, AzRHA proposed hosting an All of Us Research Program exhibit at an upcoming rural health conference in June that AZRHA is co-sponsoring (48th Annual Arizona Rural Health Conference). NRHA and our engagement counselor believe that this is the perfect opportunity to introduce the Program to Arizona rural health stakeholders. AZRHA is currently working on a Cycle 3 proposal to include this new activity. NRHA has checked with All of Us partner ASU Banner Health on their exhibitor status but have yet to receive a response; we do not want the All of Us presence to be redundant.  Moreover, the current board president of AZRHA, Elizabeth Hall -Lipsey, JD, had the brilliant idea of working with preceptors in rural areas as a way of increasing the Program’s engagement with providers and trusted health professionals in rural areas. Their involvement would also increase the involvement of the students they are working with. Both groups could then also educate and engage their clientele about the All of Us Research Program. NRHA looks forward to discussing this further in our Cycle 4 Scope of Work.   

In California, this month, NRHA met with CA State Rural Health Association president Scott Hertzberg to discuss CSRHA’s interest in a small activity as a collaborator before the end of Cycle 3 and CSRHA’s interest in participating in NRHA’s Cycle 4 programming with All of Us as a sub-awardee in the developing California Target Market. The conversation was fruitful, as the leadership was very interested to participate in All of Us programming. NRHA is awaiting a proposed budget from CSRHA for their efforts in the remainder of Cycle 3. We have decided to begin podcast engagement in Cycle 4, so we have time to plan the best fit speakers for the content.  

Finally, NRHA staff Laura Hudson participate in the quarterly Engagement Incubator. The group focused on developing games focused on the AoU Research Program that could keep partners/participants engaged and would encourage new partners/participants to join or learn more about the Program. The EI meeting allowed Mrs. Hudson to connect again with a representative from CPGI Partner PrideNet to set a time to discuss possible ways our two groups and/or or subawardees could collaborate. The meeting will take place on June 1.
column57:
NRHA continues to discuss the geographic and socioeconomic barriers individuals who live in rural areas face when attempting to participate in research such as the All of Us Research Program. NRHA has appreciated being able to discuss this with the Arizona HPO (Health Care Provider Organization), the Colorado Rural Health Center, and both groups’ engagement counselors. NRHA has discussed with the Comms team and the East Texas AHEC Waco about the best ways to share information with interested individuals specific to their geographic area at the AoU exhibit at NRHA’s Annual Conference and in general. 

NRHA has begun to discuss more with our “Rural Research Influencer” Dr. Kevin Bennett on the barriers to participation and ease of access to data by rural researchers working on the All of Us Research Program workbench.
column58:
A NRHA member expressed concern with the context of a AoU social media message NRHA posted on our Facebook page. The particular post is listed here: "LGBTQ+ individuals are 2.5 times more likely to experience depression, anxiety, and substance misuse compared to heterosexual individuals. The @AllofUsResearch Program is looking to uncover answers to disparities like this by increasing representation in research. When you #JoinAllofUs, you can help researchers find out these important answers. Get started at joinallofus.org/together #MHAM" 

The NRHA member’s comment focused on that there are “real and dangerous social conditions that can influence depression, anxiety, etc.” but that “the premise of All of Us is that genetics are the answer to everything.” 

NRHA resolved their concern by taking down the post and replying directly to our member about the Programs work on surveying for social determinants of health and included language such as, "All of Us Research Program does not just look at genetic material for their datasets and precision medicine initiative.  They have social determinants of health surveys and other types of qualitative research to address/better understand non-genetic factors to an individual’s health." and "As always, NRHA aims to work with partners such as All of Us to better understand the connection between mental and physical health and increase the representation of underserved populations in health research. That was our goal with this post, though we would be happy to discuss any additional concerns via messenger. Thanks for your feedback and for being such a valuable rural health advocate!" 

NRHA staff will talk with our engagement counselor and comms lead during our Thursday meeting more about this comment. This is a good reminder that NRHA has more opportunity to get the full message of the full scope of the Program out to our researchers and members. 
The NRHA member expressed in their comment on the post that they understood the Program to strictly define disparities through genetics. Because of this understanding, they believed that NRHA and All of Us were ignoring the social determinants of health that may contribute to the increased levels of anxiety, depression, and substance misuse in LGBTQ+ populations, as compared to heterosexual populations. 

NRHA resolved their concern by taking down the post and replying directly to our member about the Programs work on surveying for social determinants of health and included language such as, "All of Us Research Program does not just look at genetic material for their datasets and precision medicine initiative.  They have social determinants of health surveys and other types of qualitative research to address/better understand non-genetic factors to an individual’s health." and "As always, NRHA aims to work with partners such as All of Us to better understand the connection between mental and physical health and increase the representation of underserved populations in health research. That was our goal with this post, though we would be happy to discuss any additional concerns via messenger. Thanks for your feedback and for being such a valuable rural health advocate!"

column155:
May was jampacked with programming for NRHA and its sub-awardees when talking about the All of Us Research Program. Regarding information disseminations and CPGI governance activities, NRHA staff member Lea Mann has been able to represent NRHA at the Spring Engagement Meeting, Annual CPGI Meeting, target market meetings, webinars, and sub-awardee meetings. NRHA promoted the All of Us AAPI Heritage Month, Mental Health Awareness Month, National Arab American Heritage Month, and Older Americans Month social media toolkits through our platforms. NRHA also discussed a potential paid co-branded Facebook opportunity with our engagement counselor.  

Most notably, on Thursday, May 12, 2022, NRHA hosted AoU Chief Engagement Officer Dr. Karriem Watson in-person at our Annual Rural Health Conference in Albuquerque, New Mexico as the Terry Reilly Keynote Speaker. Dr. Watson presented an information session titled, “The All of Us Research Program: Engaging Rural Communities to Achieve Health Equity.” Dr. Watson successfully engaged an audience of around 200 rural health professionals with his personal journey in precision medicine research and with facts and figures on the All of Us Research Program. The audience was curious to know how the Program can and will do more to engage rural populations. Dr. Watson was able to have honest, reflective answers for the audience on how he sees the program can do more to engage rural populations in the Program. After Dr. Watson’s presentations, NRHA and TX AHEC East Waco Region waited outside the lecture hall with signs that directed the audience to engage with us if they had further questions about the Program.  

As mentioned in previous reports, at NRHA’s Annual Conference, NRHA co-hosted an All of Us Research Program exhibit with TX AHEC East, Waco Region. The Conference boasted a healthy attendance of 843 people. Ashley Bearden and Micah Bolden of TX AHEC East, Waco Region traveled to NM to staff the All of Us booth, along with NRHA staff Laura Hudson and Lea Mann. Our Engagement Counselor Rachelle Ciulla also staffed this exhibit while also assisting Dr. Watson on-site, as needed.  NRHA ordered all the Program promotional materials, as well as general exhibit assets, including a table runner & a vertical banner, needed for the conference. Texas AHEC East- Waco provided the printed materials. Also, Ms. Ciulla met with the state rural health association leaders briefly during their convening within the NRHA conference.  

In May, NRHA coordinated with our Engagement Counselor Rachelle Ciulla and our “Rural Research Influencer” Dr. Kevin Bennett to have Dr. Bennet participate in a panel on May 4, 2022, during the 2022 Spring Engagement Meeting. The panel was titled, “Building a diverse All of Us Researcher Community: Highlights of impactful engagement activities.” In this panel, Program researchers shared their impactful strategies and activities that can be used to inform future work by additional program partners. Dr. Bennett specifically spoke about the barriers when conducting rural health research on the All of Us research workbench. Dr. Bennett expressed the following barriers to conducting precision medicine research in rural populations: availability of data and equitable data; by this Dr. Bennett expanded to say that the datasets never cover all aspects of rural, as smaller areas get lost in the shuffle in larger counties that are urban. Moreover, participation from rural populations is missing because of lack of transportation or time to go to large care centers, and when they do get to the large health centers, it’s hard to talk to people because they are dealing with a myriad of other health issues. Lastly, it is hard for rural community leaders to navigate the data because they are not part of a larger university or organization that can provide support as they engage in the workbench. From this panel, we have seen positive feedback, as our Engagement Counselor Rachelle Ciulla reached out to Dr. Bennett after his panel to ask him to join a conversation with the Data Research Center (DRC), as DRC had brought up the lack of an option to stratify data for rural areas.  Our Engagement Counselor is currently coordinating with Dr. Bennett to set up a meeting between him and the DRC to discuss this lack of an option among other concerns of rural researchers on the All of Us workbench. 

This month, NRHA met with its sub-awardee the Louisiana Rural Health Association to discuss their strategy & budget for the remainder of Cycle 3. NRHA’s engagement counselor was able to join the call and have a very productive conversation with LRHA Executive Director Denae Hebert on allocating remaining funds to in-person event assets, such as a vertical banner, tablecloth, table signs, etc. LRHA plans to further connect with our Communications Counselor Rob Bartnichak about LRHA branded asset creation.  LRHA also shared the All of Us social media observances in May; those social media engagements have been entered into Network Ninja.  

In Arizona, this month, NRHA met with AZ Rural Health Association leadership to discuss their activities as collaborators for the remainder of Cycle 3 and their interest in participating in NRHA’s Cycle 4 programming with All of Us as sub-awardees and participants in the developing Arizona Target Market. From this conversation, AzRHA proposed hosting an All of Us Research Program exhibit at an upcoming rural health conference in June that AZRHA is co-sponsoring (48th Annual Arizona Rural Health Conference). NRHA and our engagement counselor believe that this is the perfect opportunity to introduce the Program to Arizona rural health stakeholders. AZRHA is currently working on a Cycle 3 proposal to include this new activity. NRHA has checked with All of Us partner ASU Banner Health on their exhibitor status but have yet to receive a response; we do not want the All of Us presence to be redundant.  Moreover, the current board president of AZRHA, Elizabeth Hall -Lipsey, JD, had the brilliant idea of working with preceptors in rural areas as a way of increasing the Program’s engagement with providers and trusted health professionals in rural areas. Their involvement would also increase the involvement of the students they are working with. Both groups could then also educate and engage their clientele about the All of Us Research Program. NRHA looks forward to discussing this further in our Cycle 4 Scope of Work.   

In California, this month, NRHA met with CA State Rural Health Association president Scott Hertzberg to discuss CSRHA’s interest in a small activity as a collaborator before the end of Cycle 3 and CSRHA’s interest in participating in NRHA’s Cycle 4 programming with All of Us as a sub-awardee in the developing California Target Market. The conversation was fruitful, as the leadership was very interested to participate in All of Us programming. NRHA is awaiting a proposed budget from CSRHA for their efforts in the remainder of Cycle 3. We have decided to begin podcast engagement in Cycle 4, so we have time to plan the best fit speakers for the content.  

Finally, NRHA staff Laura Hudson participate in the quarterly Engagement Incubator. The group focused on developing games focused on the AoU Research Program that could keep partners/participants engaged and would encourage new partners/participants to join or learn more about the Program. The EI meeting allowed Mrs. Hudson to connect again with a representative from CPGI Partner PrideNet to set a time to discuss possible ways our two groups and/or or subawardees could collaborate. The meeting will take place on June 1.

The @AllofUsResearch Program is looking to uncover answers to disparities like this by increasing representation in research. When you #JoinAllofUs, you can help researchers find out these important answers. Get started at joinallofus.org/together #MHAM"

That was our goal with this post, though we would be happy to discuss any additional concerns via messenger. Thanks for your feedback and for being such a valuable rural health advocate!"

column2: LULAC Monthly Summary Report (May 2022)
column8: League of United Latin American Citizens (LULAC)National Office
column55:
During the month of May LULAC participated in weekly check-in calls with our engagement counselor, Rima Matsumoto and communications associate Samantha Santoro. During this month LULAC was planning for the upcoming in-person cafecito in June regarding mental health. LULAC had originally planned this cafecito for May for Mental Health Awareness Month, however we experienced a few challenges with securing a space and partners in a timely manner. At the suggestion of Rima, LULAC has moved our cafecito to June 25 but will still focus on mental health as it’s an issue that should be amplified in minority communities.  LULAC also participated in the Spring Engagement Meeting and CPGI Meeting this month to better understand what other CPGI partners are doing across various markets. Additionally, LULAC made minor revisions to our CPGI Strategy Plan and submitted it to our engagement counselor through the feedback provided by the evaluation committee. We are currently awaiting next steps for the SOW development and timeline. 
Finally, Rima and the LULAC team have been discussing the execution plan for the 2022 LULAC National Convention that is taking place in San Juan, PR in late July.  We have discussed outreach and exhibiting and speaking opportunities.
column59: A challenge LULAC experienced during this month was finalizing the Mental Health Cafecito. For the month of May, LULAC had an in-person cafecito planned for the DMV market. However, we experienced challenges in finalizing a site location and participating partners.
column60: There had been some confusion last month when submitting the social media and monthly reports through Network Ninja 2.0.  During the month of May, LULAC’s Health Programs Coordinator learned how to use Network Ninja 2.0. The Programs Coordinator had a quick training session with LULAC’s engagement counselor, Rima Matsumoto on how to use the new platform.
column61: LULAC had meetings with the All of Us team throughout the month of May to discuss how to pivot the Mental Health Cafecito. Additionally, we requested support from Samantha in drafting talking points and creating social media graphics for the Mental Health Awareness Month Cafecito that will take place on June 25, 2022 in the DMV. There will be two sessions for this cafecito event– one will be in Spanish and the other in English. LULAC shared this opportunity with other CPGI partners in the DMV market call and there has been expressed interest in collaborating on this event. LULAC attended the DMV market call on May 17th and shared information about the cafecito event to other CPGI partners for an opportunity to collaborate. LULAC will also be attending the Chicago market call on May 31st. In addition to those meetings, earlier this month LULAC attended the Spring Engagement Meeting. The workshops were very informative and interesting. LULAC also attended the CPGI Meeting. It was interesting to learn more about what strategies and models worked for other CPGI partners. It was also interesting to learn about how the data is collected and given back to the CPGI partners to have a better understanding of their impact.

column2: ACCESS Monthly Summary Report (March 2022)
column55:
March featured two successful events for our team. In partnership with Henry Ford Health and Public Health Society, we hosted a tabling event at the University of Michigan-Dearborn. This event is the beginning of their spring tabling sessions, where they will raise awareness on campus regarding the research project and highlight its significance for biodiversity. 

In addition to the tabling event, further collaboration with Henry Ford and the Public Health Society included our Public Health Careers Webinar. Designed to educate students on various careers in public health, we had 90 people register. With students joining from the 3 metro-Detroit universities, speakers shared their experiences from their inspiration to enter the public health field to discussing integral work being done in the communities around us. Dr. Abdul El-Sayed presented as a keynote speaker and led the way in explaining how diverse the field can be. Both events focused on further engaging students and inviting them to join All of Us and other public health initiatives. 

We have also re-scheduled our food-series event to take place sometime in May. This event will feature a chef with a nutrition background, All of Us/ACCESS representative and a Researcher who will speak to food and culture. 

We worked closely with the marketing team to create a social media toolkit for Arab American heritage month. We intend to share these posts on the Center for Arab Narrative's social media channels as well as with other metro Detroit partners.
column59: A challenge we faced this month included how to best raise awareness regarding our webinar. This event would highlight differing public health professionals and would be a rich source of information for students. We encouraged public health professors to share this with their students broadly and invited all to attend.
column60:
From our new staff members' point of view: 

As a new member of the ACCESS & All of Us team, I am immensely excited and proud of the active community involvement ACCESS is paving. I had initially heard of the All of Us program while conducting independent research regarding medical research diversity, and now I have the opportunity to join the forefront of its mission. As an avid advocate for greater representation amongst the health field, the All of Us Program takes critical steps in the right direction. Witnessing the shared vision our community partners and collaborators have provided momentum to continue our efforts within the Metro-Detroit community. This program is vast, with numerous opportunities for discussion, sharing knowledge, and building camaraderie in the public health sphere. With continued teamwork from both ACCESS and the program, I look forward to proudly promoting medical diversity.

column62: I am a Bangladeshi American living here in suburban Detroit! I currently work for Henry Ford Health as a medical assistant and assist at a primary care clinic. Witnessing the diversity of our clientele/patients was a natural reason for me to join the All of Us program when I heard about it. It is important that communities such as mine, receive further health research attention because of how different our bodies are. Bangladeshis have different diets and lifestyles than Americans. I am happy to join this program and help the future Bangladeshi Americans and Asian communities.

column61: AHECWW staff met with Rachelle Cuilla, Engagement Counselor and WA Ecosystem Coordinator to assist with work planning and completion of reports.  The AHECWW attended the WA Ecosystem Meeting.  One of the topics was the All of Us Journey. column55: For this month of June, outreach efforts for the All of Us Research Program continues. column2: Community Council: Monthly Summary Report - June 2022
column55:
For this month of May, outreach efforts for the All of Us Research Program continues. We hosted several virtual, drive-thru, and some in-person events with all of our partners across Dallas and Houston Texas and Louisiana with virtual events extending into many other States as well. 

In Dallas, Community Council hosted a series of events, We held our annual "Dartfest" in celebration of Older American's Month, focused on educating and empowering seniors to achieve better health and wellness by introducing them to the All of Us Research Program and other resources. 

In Houston, the Harris County Area Agency on Aging and Care Connection Aging and Disability Resource Center, collaborated with Venn Strategies and the Holy Trinity Missionary Baptist Church for a community health fair. Many agencies participated from across the Houston Metropolitan area sharing information, resources, and presentations. We presented on the of the All of Us Research Program with a question-and-answer period for anyone who had questions regarding the Program. We also included the impact of chronic disease as a topic area and ended the presentation with instructions on how to join the All of Us project. We encouraged each participant to share this information with their providers and handed out the All of Us masks to attendees.    

In New Orleans, the New Orleans Council on Aging continues to provide information regarding All of Us to Senior Centers as they continue to re-open and increase their population. We also collaborated  with additional partners, such as Xavier University and LSU, in order to advance education of the All of Us Research Program.

In Shreveport, the Caddo Council on Aging held some drive-thru wellness events. Participants were able to receive information about resources and services offered in Caddo Parish. Individuals were also be able to receive COVID vaccines and information about the All of Us Research Program.

In Baton Rouge, the Capital Area Agency on Aging hosted some outreach events, as well as continue to deliver some "All of Us" material to seniors in East Feliciana Parish.
column59: As the pandemic winds down, our main challenge now, and across all our partners, is the planning of more in-person events. In the meantime, we continue to host virtual events promoting the All of Us Research Program.
