column2: Black Greek Letter Consortium/ National Pan Hellenic Council Summary June 2022
column55: During the BGLC meetings, we have been presented with feedback and training around ways we can improve our events presented in the scope of work. We have confirmed our speakers for the Table Talk series as well as identified a partner that will provide information on how to sign up as well as a more focused presentation tying the research to our subject matter. We have expanded our marketing to focus on additional ways to market our series in addition to changing our primary delivery method so that we are able to gauge attendance of our events through pre-registration. This effort will allow us to change when we deliver the pre-test i.e., during the event registration. Please note that we plan to deliver the event via Facebook live and upload it to YouTube on the NPHCTV channel.
column59: As we continue to reflect on the information, we have provided during our weekly BGLC meetings, we have made strides in developing the ideas we mentioned in the previous summary report. All messaging that we plan to use will be submitted for approval to ensure that we are staying on brand and that our messaging connects that audience not only with the subject matter of the event but how to connect with the All of Us.
column60: In the presentations we received, some of our team learned in great depth how to understand and accurately report social media metrics. While our social media coordinator usually handles all things social media, we were moved to do a deeper dive in looking at our previous events performance on social media as we prepared the Comprehensive Phase VII report. We were able to look at several demographics that helped us understand the diversity of our audience. We also confirmed that these events continue to be viewed, which confirmed for us that the concepts we provided are indeed pertinent and relevant to our desired audience.
column61: This month we participated in all BGLC Meetings. We participated in our weekly planning meetings for NPHC. We participated in and supported events hosted by other BGLC organizations. column2: Black Greek Letter Consortium/ National Pan-Hellenic Summary April 2022
column55: This month we focused on next steps for good ways to close out Phase VII and prospects. We have decided to keep our current format of the table talk series, with one change. We will be focused on health outcomes, as such we plan to include a doctor, researcher, and patient. We are shoring up partnerships with HPOs with the goal of having one partner for each event. Our plan includes keeping the events virtual except for one live event, should we be able to do an in-person event. We have had preliminary conversations with speakers for each event, with a confirmation for the first event. We continue to support the events hosted by BGLC organization as well as the Rooted in Resilience event hosted in Atlanta via Facebook live.
column59: Awareness of All of Us is a wonderful opportunity to engage in selfcare on a deeper level. The challenges we face relates to how to develop informative information that highlights the purpose of the All of Us program as well as engage our community in selfcare and personal health advocacy. All of Us program participation is an important tool, that could be used to help our community members understand how to advocate for themselves. This is the primary reason why we have decided to update our table talk series to ensure that we include a researcher, a doctor, and a patient. This is the new format we will use going forward.
column60: The theme for this month’s lessons includes end use experience with the program, which directly informs how we develop our table talk. A member of the team who is a participant in the program, had an extensive conversation about the Social Determinants of Health Survey in the portal. According to the representative, they were reaching out to people who had not completed the survey to get it completed as well as understand their hesitation with completing the survey. It seems that although there have been great strides in getting people engaged, there is still work to do in keeping people engaged in the activities and the project.   This helped our team members have a greater understanding about the direction of the program and our work with All of Us.
column61: This month we participated in all BGLC Meetings. We participated in our weekly planning meetings for NPHC. We participated in and supported events hosted by other BGLC organizations. We reviewed the CPGI New Cycle Planning packet, where we noted with interest that Chicago is on the list of market cities. Finally, we engaged with an HPO in a discussion about the participant experience specifically as it relates to the Social Determinants of Health Survey. This conversation was held by a team member is a participant with the HPO where they are signed up.

column55: For the period between the end of June 2022 and the Month of July 2022 we attended and participated in all BGLC calls and AOU monthly calls along with planning events and calls for our different health-related events with our partners. We attended collaborative event meetings as well as discussions on the next potential phase of the program. Participated in discussions on best practices for events as well as retainment of participants. Assisted with shipping and receiving of assets for people-facing events being held in Metro Atlanta. Held planning strategy meetings with our external partners to collaborate on the program with our other Health and Wellness events. Assisted with local events within the market as well as participated in the communication meetings for the next phase. Participated in and completed surveys for upcoming diversity discussions.

column2: AAPA / April 2022 Monthly Summary Report
column55:
The following activities are currently underway or in preparation stages:
- Communications/social media: Monthly social media posts on AAPA/PA Foundation channels - 4/1, 4/7, 4/25. Incorporated messaging related to National Minority Health Month, World Health Day, and social determinants of health (toolkit). Communications article published on AAPA News Central (4/4) - wrap-up/recap of live webinar event featuring All of Us, with CTA to access CME bundle (including recorded webinar and two additional recorded segments) on AAPA Learning Central. Promoted via social media posts on AAPA channels (shared on PAF channels).
- Nutrition collaboration: Continuing coordination for collaborative activity with Black Women's Health Imperative. PA Nutrition Outreach Fellows followed up with BWHI re: potential activities this month; BWHI outlined opportunities scheduled for end of April and summer 2022. Possible collaborative activity with ACCESS Detroit - no update since engagement counselor sent introductory email in mid-November; plan is to identify Nutrition Outreach Fellow(s) to give presentation. Possible webinar with Denver YMCA - no update since last email exchange in October (waiting on their response/follow-up).
- CME sessions (AoU conference session, research session, and Genetics & Genomics CME bundle): Enduring sessions on AAPA Learning Central; continuing to collect/compile participation metrics on a monthly basis.
- AAPA Conference 2022 digital ads: Digital All of Us banner ad running on conference registration site; will run through May 2022. In-person conference activity - Display will be a free-standing double-sided meter board sign with accompanying brochure holder. Finalized NIH approval process for banner artwork; submitted for production. Finalized tweaks to healthcare provider brochure template (via comms counselor) and placed print order. 
- Student programming at AAPA Conference 2022 (student seminar): Planning process continuing. Pyxis helped us identify alternate speaker to replace Dr .Watson: JoAnn Smith. Held planning/run-through call with speakers to go over program flow, content, and logistics (4/12). Set deadline for slide deck submission and scheduled final pre-event call  for 5/10.
- Web/digital placement - Will run digital ad in May 5 edition of PA-Central Member (newsletter distributed to AAPA member audience). Worked with communications counselor to select ad and update copy for healthcare provider audience ("Help your patients tell their story").
- Website landing pages: Continuing to collect monthly metrics.
- Other activities (outside SOW): Identified PA to participate in healthcare provider module filming (4/5). Promotion of collaborative webinar with National Alliance for Hispanic Health, scheduled for May 5 - placement in MedWatch newsletter (4/18); PA-Central Student newsletter (4/19).
column59: Challenges included pivoting/making adjustments for our in-person student symposium event based on the news that our original speaker could no longer participate. We remained in communication with the Pyxis team, with regular follow-up/check-ins, and they assisted us in identifying a new speaker.
column60: We received more tangible evidence that the All of Us program is of interest to the PA audience, based on the audience engagement during our Women in Philanthropy webinar event on precision medicine and women's health. Audience members asked questions after the presentation that indicated interest in learning more and potentially getting involved. We also received outreach from a PA expressing his interest in getting more involved in the program in a direct way.
column62: An article and series of social media posts highlighting a PA who works in genetic medicine generated high levels of engagement. Genetic medicine is a lesser-know/less common practice area for PAs, and seemed to spark interest among our audience. We tied All of Us messaging into the article to provide an overview of the program and encourage PAs interested in genetics to consider getting involved, including on the research side.

column156: Challenges included pivoting/making adjustments for our in-person student symposium event based on the news that our original speaker could no longer participate. We remained in communication with the Pyxis team, with regular follow-up/check-ins, and they assisted us in identifying a new speaker.
column157: We received more tangible evidence that the All of Us program is of interest to the PA audience, based on the audience engagement during our Women in Philanthropy webinar event on precision medicine and women's health. Audience members asked questions after the presentation that indicated interest in learning more and potentially getting involved. We also received outreach from a PA expressing his interest in getting more involved in the program in a direct way.
column159: An article and series of social media posts highlighting a PA who works in genetic medicine generated high levels of engagement. Genetic medicine is a lesser-know/less common practice area for PAs, and seemed to spark interest among our audience. We tied All of Us messaging into the article to provide an overview of the program and encourage PAs interested in genetics to consider getting involved, including on the research side.

column59:
challenges included staff transitions both at the national and local level for CenterLink and our sub awardees.  Bringing new staff on board and bringing center staff and team up to date on the project requires time and ongoing TA communication. The challenges were address by providing on going TA, and holding an ongoing meeting to bring all staff up to date on deliverables as well as an understanding of administrative processes and partnerships.

Another challenge has been managing communications and requests to participate in events and presentations within short periods of time and/or outside of our scopes of work for both our subs and ourselves.  This challenge has been communicated and addressed to the best of our ability. We plan to account for some of these activities within scopes of work for the next cycles as this program continues to grow and partnerships continue to develop.

Lastly, both Facebook and Twitter have repeatedly rejected posts to the platform, citing none-compliance with their rules/regulations; this is simply not sure, and we believe it has to do with the use of certain hashtags (#LGBTQ). Contessa and the Clyde team have been alerted to this and their staff is closely working with us

column2: Community Council: Monthly Summary Report - April 2022
column55:
For this month of March, outreach efforts for the All of Us Research Program continues. We hosted several virtual, drive-thru, and some in-person events with all of our partners across Dallas and Houston Texas and Louisiana with virtual events extending into many other States as well. 

In Dallas, Community Council hosted a series of virtual events, such as "Healthy Cooking" and TSU’s "Medical Mistrust and Vaccine Hesitancy" each one focused on educating and empowering communities to achieve better health and wellness by introducing them to the All of Us Research Program. We also participated in a local food bank, with our Community Relations Manager, Patricia Johnson, attending to help out the community, while informing them about the All of Us Research Program. 

In Houston, the Harris County Area Agency on Aging and Care Connection Aging and Disability Resource Center, collaborated with Wellsville YMCA to do a Healthy Living Class. They discussed healthy recipes that are easy to make. For the participants, they made a turkey wrap with cranberries and discussed the vulnerable population, and chronic disease. They also discussed All of Us and how to join the research project. They encouraged each participant to tell their doctors about the All of Us Research Program.  At the end of the session, All of Us face masks were distributed.  

In New Orleans, the New Orleans Council on Aging continues to provide information regarding All of Us to Senior Centers as they continue to re-open and increase their population. They will also be collaborating with additional partners next month, such as Dillard University and LSU, in order to advance education of the All of Us Research Program.

In Shreveport, the Caddo Council on Aging held some drive-thru wellness events. Participants were able to receive information about resources and services offered in Caddo Parish. Individuals were also be able to receive COVID vaccines and information about the All of Us Research Program.

In Baton Rouge, the Capital Area Agency on Aging hosted some outreach events, as well as continue posting "All of Us" blog posts on their home page. They were also able to deliver some All of Us material to seniors in East Feliciana Parish. They also are continuing to plan an event with Pennington and the YMCA for May (Date subject to change)
column59: COVID continues to be the main challenge across all our partners, but with more and more restrictions being lifted, we are starting to plan more in-person events. In the meantime, we continue to host virtual events promoting the All of Us Research Program.
column60: As always, we continue to learn of more engaging ways to work alongside different organizations and communities, to keep participants engaged and aware of the All of Us Research Program. The monthly meetings with other partners brings synergy with a focus on creative outreach and innovative in our methods of targeting new partnerships.

column2: AHECWW at Whatcom/April 2022 Monthly Summary Report
column55: The AHEC has delivered 3 out of 4 large conference and exhibition events.  The center continues to develop a better understanding of how AHECs can support the All of Us program through our experience and the opportunities provided by Pyxis to collaborate with AHEC/THEARI and the WA Ecosystem.
column57: The main challenge is capacity at this time.  However, the AHEC is actively working to address this issue.
column58:
Center capacity has been a challenge this year.  It was expected that center staff would need to be flexible to delivery of media work on virtual and in-person events.  However, the challenges of staffing and hiring during the pandemic were new with many organizations in the AHEC network impacted by the great resignation.  This had internal implications, but also impacted AHEC external partners and contacts. 

The AHEC hired two more part-time hourly staff in March and spent time onboarding and training during the month of April.  This was challenging to administer during our planned travel months for the All of Us Program, but also a positive for the center. Lesly Pumay was added to the All of Us program grant work at the center to support social media work. She is graduating this year with a BFA in Design from Cornish College of Arts.  The AHECWW working diligently to launch a social media campaign as a part of our All of Us grant before the close of the fiscal year. 

The center also interviewed candidates and hired one new full-time position to start in May. These efforts will significantly improve center capacity across grant work. The AHECWW continues to push forward identifying strategies to maintain and deliver grant tasks to the best of staff ability and capacity, while addressing any deficiencies
column59:
During the Western Forum, Cori Garcia Hansen became ill with an upper respiratory infection.  She was then not allowed to participate in the in-person conference.  However, the AHECWW center sent two staff, so Carlos Morales, was able to cover the event activities.  The AHECWW also had the support of the National Alliance for Hispanic Health.  Overall, the task was delivered successfully.   

As the AHECWW looks forward to the opportunity to continue participation with the All of Us Program, the center has reflected on its niche and role in the work in the WA Ecosystem.  The education and awareness piece seems complimentary to the work to build support among health professionals working in underserved communities.  Ultimately, this will help with recruitment and retention.  We also continue to provide information about the research work bench to the health professions student and professional audience. The AHEC needs to learn more about how to best evaluate and survey participants in programming to serve the other collaborative efforts in the region and goals of the program.  As the development of the WA Ecosystem group is new, the center is optimistic about the opportunities to collaborate and form a streamlined approach with tangible outcomes in support of regional partners.
column60: With the ongoing challenges during the pandemic, the experience with event coverage demonstrated the importance of back-up plans and staffing when unforeseen factors like illness impact the work.
column61: The AHECWW participated in the CPGI Engagement Counseling meeting and the National AHEC Organization All of Us Program presentation. These meetings were very helpful in event prep and with  completing the AHECWW  New Cycle Planning Packet.  The AHECWW did not attend the AHEC/THEARI meeting, as this was during the Western Forum. This meeting time was used for the other AHECs to practice for their collaborative presentation on the student ambassador program, which the AHECWW currently does not provide.
column62: Thus far, the AHECWW is finding that participant engagement best-resonating messages are about opportunities to engage in research.  This makes sense, as AHECs primarily work with students and health professionals who are passionate about service to underserved communities and improving healthcare for these populations.

column57: Also...Closing our current grantee status after two years due to changing status of internal GAHEC organization developments. Personally, I will be continuing to advocate within our community and region awareness and opportunities related to the work of the All of Us Research Program as able and hope to regain momentum as a partner in the future, so will be advocating for the AoU Program to continue this work to foster awareness with healthcare contacts and to our GAHEC partners in academic and healthcare agencies.

column59: NA, except GAHEC staffing in transition and preparing for full office move and going digital re: time/resources internally
column60:
Progress of AoU over past month, including reaching the milestone of a half-million enrollees 
That All of Us has fostered a culture of an open-door policy to expand its networks and support all possible involvement and sharing whenever possible, within their infrastructure and mission focus, and how the organization is always growing to advance this initiative with maintaining the focus of the underserved and under-represented being brought to the top of the research chain for improving healthcare more effectively.
column61:
This month provided a unique opportunity for the return of our statewide NC AHEC Nurse Council to reconvene for their bi-annual, in-person strategic planning meeting for the first time since pre-pandemic for two days. It consisted of nursing leaders/education and program coordinators from all nine AHEC centers, the UNC-CH School of Nursing and the NC AHEC Program Office at UNC-Chapel Hill. GAHEC was able to exhibit with AoU signage and multiple fliers, while providing picture frame magnets, note pads and tote bags. GAHEC hosted a half-day program for health careers with middle school students and included notepad giveaways and program information in Rockingham County, which is more rural area.
We were able to use our virtual webinar conference exhibitor package for a large and diverse audience of healthcare providers from more than 50 cities in NC that was a program on “The Ethics of Critical Race Theory: Addressing Equity in Schools and the Impact on Families” in partnership with the UNC-Chapel Hill School of Social Work.

column2: NHMA Monthly Summary June 2022
column55:
As NHMA wraps up this project year, we continued the momentum of returning back to in-person events. On June 8th, 2022, NHMA held a provider-focused roundtable in our new office. NHMA received 13 registrants and 2 people who showed up.  Additionally, NHMA collaborated with LULAC, Mary's Center, and NHCOA to participate in a health fair in-person at CASA in Maryland. The event featured tabling, giveaways, and cafecitos in English and Spanish. NHMA sent three representatives to support the event and set up a table to give out NHMA branded bags, HIV materials, and All of Us incentives that were still remaining after our conference in March. Virtually, NHMA continued to post on social media and launched the Facebook Ad Takeover campaign with the help of our EC and the Clyde Group. NHMA also continued active participation on partner calls, target market calls, meetings with our EC and the CPGI webinar. NHMA completed the final month of All of Us content inclusion within our monthly newsletter.

In preparation for our new project year, NHMA has been soliciting and creating a list of interested physicians and NHMA chapters to leverage for inclusion in our efforts.
column59: NHMA did not experience any challenges this month.
column60: Despite a disappointing turnout for our provider roundtable on June 8th, NHMA, our EC, and Jakara Eason, along with other Pyxis staff, had a very productive discussion with George Zangaro and Colleen Leners from AACN. NHMA learned that the program is continuing to encourage partners to start enrolling participants and researchers. Dr. Leners had great experiences and insights from working with HPO's in the past and it was helpful to learn more about how that process looks on the ground in certain regions, and how partnerships are established. It helped to paint a better picture of the CPGI role and the role of the HPO's and how the work flow is typically handled. Dr. Leners emphasized the importance of following up with potential participants immediately after the event, the advantages of Ipads at events, and the crucial role that QR codes played at in-person events.
column61: This month, NHMA met Rima Matsumoto on June 2nd, where she informed us about the LULAC in-person health fair opportunity, which we were extremely excited to participate in. On June 9th, NHMA met with the other partners who agreed to participate in the LULAC health fair at CASA. On June 13th, NHMA participated in the CPGI webinar where we learned about enrollment updates and the MSRS in March/April. The following day, NHMA attended the New York Target Market Call. On June 15th. NHMA met with our EC briefly for a check-in and to introduce our EC to our new Director of Programs, Yvonne Malloy, MPP. ON the 21st of June, NHMA also attended the DMV Target Market Call.

column2: NHMA Monthly Summary April 2022
column55:
In regards to this project, NHMA completed and submitted the engagement strategy for the new cycle on the designated due date to our EC. NHMA also began to plan the Cinco de Mayo office housewarming event where we plan to distribute All of Us materials that we had in surplus from the NHMA Annual Conference. Registration and promotion has already begun.

The NHMA programs and communications team completed the deliverable of incorporating two webpages about All of Us into our new resource hub, HispanicHealth.info. NHMA developed two pages to target different target audiences within our network. One page was developed for patients and one was developed for researchers and physicians. Both pages were carefully crafted to contain easily digestible text and visual images that helped to break down the program. On the patient side, we focused on keeping the information culturally competent and at a health literacy level that matches our communities needs. This page broke down how to join the program step by step and what the journey looks like with images along the way. The provider side consisted of information about the program that could be relayed to their patients, privacy concerns, and also how they can join as researchers. NHMA worked closely with our EC and  our Account Supervisor from the Clyde group to ensure proper protocols and messaging were executed.
Patient Side: https://hispanichealth.info/all-of-us-participants/
Provider Side: https://hispanichealth.info/all-of-us-providers/

In preparation for the new cycle, NHMA also reached out to chapter leaders in target markets to gauge interest in the program and participating in events for the new cycle. NHMA received interest from 3 chapters in Texas, Arizona, and California,  and received interest from 3 physician researchers to be potential spokespersons. NHMA also established a connection with Mary's Center in DC for potential collaboration opportunities for the new cycle.
column59: NHMA faced the challenge of having to elaborate on the engagement strategy document for how we would track researcher engagement and outcomes. We revised our approach and potential outcomes to align with the program's goals and hope to receive more feedback and strategies for enhancing this activity.
column60: This month, NHMA learned the importance of establishing partnerships for collaborations with HPO's in our target market areas and where we have chapters. We also learned the importance of planning in advance with chapters and interested physicians/researcher to get them involved with our scope of work for the upcoming project period.
column61:
On April 6, 2022, NHMA's core project team, including President & CEO, Dr. Elena Rios, met with our EC to discuss the engagement strategy document. During the call, we discussed best practices for submissions, collaborations with local HPO's in the DMV, and tracking researcher and participant engagement using coded target market links.

On April 12 and April 19, 2022, NHMA was present for the New York Target Market Call and the DMV Target Market Call. NHMA shared our recent conference and our upcoming Cinco de Mayo event on the DMV Call. NHMA and Mary's Center connected via email after the call for potential partnerships. The organizations will be meeting during the week of May 2nd. NHMA invited our EC to the call.

On April 20, 2022, NHMA staff met with our EC and Jakara Eason to discuss the possibility of hosting an event in our new office space in June. Planning has  begun and NHMA is meeting internally to decide on a date for the provider roundtable. NHMA plans to have Dr. Elena Rios participate as a speaker and also plans to help promote the event to our networks and local chapter. On April 27, 2022, NHMA participated in the Louisiana Engagement Network Meeting.

column2: Xavier University-June 2022 Monthly Report
column55:
We completed our third training on the All of Us Workbench on Saturday, June 4, 2022. The training was well attended by UBR faculty, students and our guest UBR faculty from FAMU.
On June 9, 2022 Dr. Lemieux presented the AoURP to first year pharmacy students course (Biotechnology and Pharmacogenomics, PHSC 3650). The course has a total of 38 students. On June 16, 2022, Dr. Lemieux presented the AoURP to the College of Pharmacy's Center Of Excellence Pre-matriculation program of 32 students.

column2: Black Greek Letter Consortium/  Iota Phi Theta Summary April 2022
column55: For the month of April, Iota Phi Theta Fraternity, Inc. completed our entitled “Precision Medicine Takes Center Stage” which was performed on Wednesday, March 27th, 2022.  The spoken word pieces from Ms. Ciara Edwards (love of Black Men) and Mr. Arris Cohen (Veggie Gangstas, a tribute to healthy eating) were very well received. The painting created by Mr. Searius Addishin was presented as a gift to BGLC Coordinator Ms. Jennifer Jones as a tribute for all of the hard work she has put in over the years.  In addition to the artists, the conversation with former International Grand Polaris Robert M. Clark Jr. and his wife Felita Clark hit home as they talked about the areas of stress, relationships, and even the Grammys.  Members of Iota also participated on all weekly BGLC calls as well as began to plan for the next phase of activations as discussed on our weekly calls.  We also distributed the information from the upcoming Rooted in Research Program in Atlanta, GA to that Region and he’s gotten the word out to the local chapters there.  Finally, we met with BGLC to go over the next potential phase of programming which will focus on Gerontology and the Senior population
column59: None
column60: We have started planning for our upcoming event in June as we will be focusing on Black Men’s Health.  The focus will be on going to the Doctor and having conversations with the coordinators of the different D9 fraternities about their views on Men’s Health
column61: For this month of April, the brothers of Iota Phi Theta Fraternity, Inc. have set in motion plans to create a program for the month of June focusing on Men & Their Health.  We also met with the BGLC leadership about our next proposed phase of activities.  The focus we have in mind, after reading the 5-year mission of the program, is on Gerontology and our Elder population.  The reasoning behind this is that we have a lot of older brothers in our fraternity (one more living Founder) and it’s time we begin to talk about being there for them during this time of need.  Thinking of this makes it even more important that we educate the public about the importance of Precision Medicine and taking care of our loved ones in their Golden Years.  As of right now, the cities we are targeting for in-person launches are Houston, Denver, and Detroit.
column62: Mixing up of message delivery is the most productive as doing this catches the eye of different people so now they begin asking questions (carrot & stick approach)

column2: Faith-Based Genetic Research Institute/May 2022 Monthly Report
column55:
A) On behalf of the Faith Based Genetic Research Institute, Dr. Tshaka Cunningham participated as a keynote Speaker at the Community Partner Spring Engagement Meeting on May 5, 2022. Dr. Cunningham recorded and provided a video presentation entitled "My “Why”: Genomics Journey" where he discussed his personal motivations as a member of a historically underrepresented minority group (African-American) for participating in genomic research studies such as the NIH All of Us Program. He also shared information with participants on the background of genomics research and the importance of recruiting more diverse participants for genomic research studies in order to make the resulting data more relevant to all US citizens. In addition to providing the recording for this meeting, Dr. Cunningham attended the virtual meeting online and participated in several of the breakout room sessions throughout. 


B) On behalf of the Faith Based Genetic Research Institute, Dr. Cunningham provided content for an interview for Diversity In Action Magazine. Dr. Cunningham responded to a variety of interview questions about the importance of recruiting diverse participants for genomic research studies and highlighted specific strategies for engaging African-American communities in churches and other public gatherings. Dr. Cunningham specifically highlighted the importance of minority individuals participating in the NIH All of Us program, with the hope of inspiring those in their readership to participate.


C) Dr. Tshaka Cunningham, the Executive Director of the Faith Based Genetic Institute, was featured in a short film called "Finding Faith in Science" produced by iBiology & the Wonder Collaborative (see youtube link: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=HyDR7eC63ss) that highlights his journey as a scientist and person of faith and shares information on the importance of diverse populations participating in genetics research. This link for this video content was shared by Dr. Cunningham on various social media platforms and posted on the fbgri.org website.

column2: NRHA / Cycle 3 April 2022 Monthly Summary Report
column55:
April of Cycle 3 has been a busy month for NRHA as we finalized our Cycle 4 Strategy document while also finalizing the remaining Cycle 3 activities. In regard to information disseminations and CPGI governance activities, NRHA staff member Lea Mann has been able to represent NRHA at the target market meetings, webinars, and sub-awardee meetings. NRHA promoted the All of Us DNA Day and World Health Day social media toolkits through our platforms. NRHA also discussed a potential paid co-branded Facebook opportunity with our engagement counselor, , communications counselor, and internal NRHA staff. Further, NRHA was able to share with its sub-awardees a social media analytics tracking form that is enhancing NRHA’s social media reporting in Network Ninja.  

In Colorado, our sub-awardee the Colorado Rural Health Center (CRHC) held their Annual Rural Health Forum April 6-8, 2022. The Forum provided an opportunity for Colorado’s 55 certified Rural Health Clinics, and other rural providers and healthcare professionals interested in learning more about rural specific healthcare to convene, learn, and network together. NRHA and CRHC wanted to take the opportunity to educate rural providers on what the Program is and why it is safe and important to participate in the All of Us Research Program. NRHA, with the help of our engagement counselor, was able to coordinate an All of Us presence at the Forum, which consisted of Denver Market Coordinator Julia Daverne giving an oral presentation on the AoU Research Program, as well as Ms. Daverne hosting an All of Us Research Program exhibit space. It was reported back to NRHA by CRHC that after the Forum, 50% of survey respondents said they would like more sessions on diversity and inclusion in the future, which was a central topic in the AoU Research Program session. Please see the Network Ninja activities log for more information about the exhibit and the session.  Finally, here are highlights Ms. Daverne also shared upon return from the Forum:  

“I just returned from an amazing trip to Denver, CO to speak and exhibit at the Colorado Rural Health Center Forum. I met attendees from various professional backgrounds which included providers/MDs/nurses, a hospital CEO, clinic directors...etc. I had great introductory conversations about the All of Us program while exhibiting. 19 attendees were in my session which was great given the average was about 15 for concurrent sessions. I met many of the attendees at the table and incorporated their stories into the presentation. It was great learning about rural populations! I met Amanda Quintana with NAHN, who was awesome to meet in person. She attended the AoU session and added great supportive AoU commentary to the discussion.” 

On April 25th, NRHA subawardee, the Louisiana Rural Health Association, in accordance with their goals to have a larger social media presence, participated in the DNA Day Twitter Chat with the University of Shreveport in the Shreveport, LA Market. LRHA also shared the All of Us social media observances in April. Those social media engagements have/will be entered into Network Ninja.  

In the El Paso, TX Target Market, Krista Forbes, target market coordinator, has assisted NRHA in identifying existing CHW AoU materials. While NRHA had anticipated being further along in the development of a rural CHW training related to AoU in Cycle 3, we encountered some unforeseen challenges and therefore reallocated some funding to support All of Us Research Program’s presence at NRHA’s Annual Conference.  NRHA has contracted with Janel Lowman, a CHW trainer who has worked with rural CHWS and is familiar with the Program through her position with the University of South Alabama, to develop an outline for rural CHW training from the existing All of Us Research Program slide decks with the sole purpose of educating rural CHWs about the Program. Upon successful completion of this outline in Cycle 3, NRHA proposes to build upon the outline in Cycle 4 to create AoU Research Program training modules for rural CHWs.  

As noted in the previous reports, NRHA is delighted to have Dr. Watson present the Terry Reilly Keynote at the NRHA 2022 Annual Rural Health Conference on Thursday, May 12, 2022 in Albuquerque, NM. We continue to work with our engagement counselor and communications lead to coordinate the All of Us presence at the Annual Conference. Since Dr. Watson is attending the Annual Rural Health Conference, NRHA has been working with CPGI Partner Texas AHEC East, Waco office to finalize details for the co-hosted exhibit. Our Engagement Counselor Rachelle Ciulla will be helping to support this exhibit while also assisting Dr. Watson on-site, if needed. NRHA also plans to engage conference participants directly after Dr. Watson’s presentation to take any additional questions or comments they may have about the AoU Research Program by holding “Ask Me a Question” signs outside of the auditorium. The plans and efforts continue to be ongoing as the date of the Annual Conference is approaching. NRHA has ordered all of the Program promotional materials, as well as general exhibit assets, including a table runner & a vertical banner, needed for the conference. Texas AHEC East- Waco will be providing the printed materials. Also, Ms. Ciulla will meet with the state rural health association leaders briefly during their convening within the NRHA conference. 

In April, NRHA has been in conversation with our “Rural Research Influencer” Dr. Kevin Bennett about coordinating an online seminar based around the All of Us Research Program’s Workbench. This would take place before the end of Cycle 3 – likely in June 2022.  

In Arizona, this month, NRHA met with AZ Rural Health Association leadership to discuss their activities as collaborators for the remainder of Cycle 3 and their interest in participating in NRHA’s Cycle 4 programming with All of Us as subawardees and participants in the developing Arizona Target Market. From this conversation, AzRHA proposed hosting an All of Us Research Program exhibit at an upcoming rural health conference in June that AZRHA is co-sponsoring (48th Annual Arizona Rural Health Conference). NRHA and our engagement counselor believe that this is the perfect opportunity to introduce the Program to Arizona rural health stakeholders. AZRHA is currently working on a Cycle 3 proposal to include this new activity. Moreover, the current board president of AZRHA, Elizabeth Hall -Lipsey, JD, had the brilliant idea of working with preceptors in rural areas as a way of increasing the Program’s engagement with providers and trusted health professionals in rural areas. Their involvement would also increase the involvement of the students they are working with. Both groups could then also educate and engage their clientele about the All of Us Research Program. NRHA looks forward to discussing this further in our Cycle 4 Scope of Work.   

In California, this month, NRHA met with CA State Rural Health Association president Scott Hertzberg to discuss CSRHA’s interest in a small activity as a collaborator before the end of Cycle 3 and CSRHA’s interest in participating in NRHA’s Cycle 4 programming with All of Us as a subawardee in the developing California Target Market. The conversation was fruitful, as the leadership was very interested to participate in All of Us programming. They mentioned having a podcast series in which they would be happy to feature information and figures from the Program to familiarize their audience with the Program. They suggested maybe including other California CPGI, HPO, or National Partners on the podcast. NRHA is waiting to hear back from the president, who was seeking approval from the full CSRHA Board.
column57: NRHA continues to discuss the geographic and socioeconomic barriers individuals who live in rural areas face when attempting to participate in research such as the All of Us Research Program. NRHA has appreciated being able to discuss this with the Arizona HPO (Health Care Provider Organization), the Colorado Rural Health Center, and both groups’ engagement counselors. NRHA has discussed with the Comms team and the East Texas AHEC Waco about the best ways to share information with interested individuals specific to their geographic area at the AoU exhibit at NRHA’s Annual Conference and in general.
column58: There are challenges that we hope to explore in Cycle 4: When working with trusted community partners like providers or other groups, what type of information do they need to feel comfortable sharing about the importance of enrollment in the AoU Program? What would make a provider recommend this program to a patient? How can NRHA assist in coordinating these types of discussions between rural providers and the Program? How can NRHA better identify UBR groups within rural (I.e., someone who is a person of color living in rural America or an LGBTQ+ person living in rural America), essentially how do we take into better account the intersectional identities of people that cause them to be further underrepresented in biomedical precision research?
column59:
NRHA was hoping to All of Us Research Program promotional giveaways at the CRHC 2022 Forum,   unfortunately there was a technical glitch that caused the order not to be processed. When the CRHC order modification was submitted in the system, it did not alert the appropriate staff person as it was designed to do; therefore that the modified was not processed. NRHA was alerted by our engagement counselor that the items did not get shipped in time because of the glitch. NRHA and Pyxis have decided to ship those giveaways to a future NRHA or subawardee in-person All of Us event. We appreciate our engagement counselor and the system monitor’s help in figuring out the issue and working to correct it in the system.  

As mentioned in the accomplishments section, NRHA had planned to have developed the rural community health worker training activity further this cycle, but staff transition and the realization that the type of CHW materials we were looking for did not exist, have delayed our progress on this activity. However, a CHW trainer is now developing an outline for a CHW training using the approved AoU Research Program slide deck. We plan to build upon that work in our proposed scope of work for Cycle 4. In consultation with our engagement counselor, funding that had been set aside for the CHW trainer was reallocated to support AoU’s session at NRHA’s Annual Conference.
column60: NRHA has learned that collaboration and maintaining reachable goals can lead to success! On the other side of this lesson is that collaboration and maintaining reachable goals requires patience, flexibility, and open communication. Unfortunately, we were unable to have the promotional giveaways at the Forum, but now have also learned an important lesson to follow up after submission to confirm receipt and that there is always a way to repurpose materials.
column61: Between March, 31, 2022, and April 30, 2022, NRHA has communicated with our engagement counselor, Rachelle Ciulla, weekly. NRHA has worked with sub-awardees on activities and had internal discussions about sub-awardee priorities related to the project including considering additional target markets for the next cycle proposal. Internal meetings have also been discussed regarding upcoming communication activities.  NRHA staff were able to attend all Target Market meetings, the All of Us Researchers Convention, all Cycle 4 planning meetings and all other virtual events held by the Program.

column2: Texas AHEC East - Waco Region / July 2022 Monthly Summary Report
column55: Our accomplishments this moth stem from the AoU Student Ambassador Program with our current Ambassador tabling at two New Student Conferences and increasing the exposure of the program to a diverse group of individuals.
column57: The greatest barriers to participation is the push for enrollment and a misunderstanding by the program of where we are truly located (Texas is BIG). We are located 2 hours from Dallas so we are working to cover all of the Central Texas space, and our nearest enrollment partner is in Temple which is 45 minutes away. Encouraging potential participants to enroll when they will inevitably need to travel 90 minutes round trip to get the more exciting pieces of the program/data isn't very likely to happen as participants only receive a $25 gift card which doesn't even cover the cost of gas. The enrollment center is also only open during regular business hours Monday - Friday. So even if individuals were willing to travel for enrollment and giving those data pieces, the time frame for enrollment does not work for most people. We are very uniquely located to where we can work to connect the current target markets (a lot of rural space), however the program hasn't caught up to our need/understanding of the unique placement and how we can truly connect Central Texas which is largely missed at the moment.
column58: Ability to enroll participants. We are technically in an HPO market, but are truly more of a DV market partner that hasn't had the DV materials.
column59: Our Ambassador stated that delays and unforeseen circumstances in pre-scheduled events, as well as lack of responses from new community organizations were his greatest challenge this month. He is addressing this by increasing his communications with organizations as well as this Waco AHEC.
column60: Having contingency plans for scheduled events is a crucial skill to avoid delays and productivity slumps is a great lesson learned by our Student Ambassador this month.

column2: Community Council: Monthly Summary Report - May 2022
column55:
For this month of April, outreach efforts for the All of Us Research Program continues. We hosted several virtual, drive-thru, and some in-person events with all of our partners across Dallas and Houston Texas and Louisiana with virtual events extending into many other States as well. 

In Dallas, Community Council hosted a series of events, we held the last segment of our "Healthy Cooking" virtual show, as well as two in-person events “Family Fit Fest” and “Cinco de Mayo Celebration” focused on educating and empowering communities to achieve better health and wellness by introducing them to the All of Us Research Program and other resources. 

In Houston, the Harris County Area Agency on Aging and Care Connection Aging and Disability Resource Center, collaborated with St. Matthews Church. “Coffee and Croissants”, ADRC discussed how the Area Agency on Aging and Care Connection utilizes All of Us Research Project to connect with the community.  We discussed the vulnerable population, and chronic disease. We also discussed All of Us and how to join the research project. We encouraged each participant to tell their doctors about All of Us as well as handed out masks.  

In New Orleans, the New Orleans Council on Aging continues to provide information regarding All of Us to Senior Centers as they continue to re-open and increase their population. They will also be collaborating with additional partners next month, such as Xavier University and LSU, in order to advance education of the All of Us Research Program.

In Shreveport, the Caddo Council on Aging held some drive-thru wellness events. Participants were able to receive information about resources and services offered in Caddo Parish. Individuals were also be able to receive COVID vaccines and information about the All of Us Research Program.

In Baton Rouge, the Capital Area Agency on Aging hosted some outreach events, as well as continue posting "All of Us" blog posts on their home page. They were also able to deliver some All of Us material to seniors in East Feliciana Parish.
column59: Remaining COVID restrictions continue to be the main challenge across all our partners, but with more and more restrictions being lifted, we are starting to plan more in-person events. In the meantime, we continue to host virtual events promoting the All of Us Research Program.
column60: As always, we continue to learn of more engaging ways to work alongside different organizations and communities. The monthly meetings with other partners brings synergy with a focus on creative outreach and innovative in our methods of targeting new partnerships. Throughout this project year, we are learning to be creative and innovative in our methods of fostering new partnerships. We are also learning to be resourceful and to think outside of the box when it comes to capturing the attention of the community.

column2: LULAC Monthly Summary Report (April 2022)
column8: League of United Latin American Citizens (LULAC)National Office
column55:
During the month of April, LULAC participated in weekly check-in calls with our new engagement counselor Rima Matsumoto as Liz Hurtado was transitioning out. During this month LULAC was planning for the upcoming in-person cafecito in May for Mental Health Awareness Month. LULAC began looking for potential venues and partner organizations in the DMV area. LULAC is just awaiting confirmation on the location from our potential co-host in order to confirm the date in June. Additionally, we have developed a final list of potential speakers that we are also reaching out to for the invitation to join our panels and began discussing with Samantha Santoro, our communications counselor our needs for promotional materials.  During the DMV market call on April 19, 2022 LULAC shared information regarding the in-person cafecito and opportunities for collaboration. Additionally, during this month LULAC worked on the CPGI Strategy Plan to submit by the April 8, 2022 deadline. With Rima’s guidance, we were able to align LULAC’s strategies with the All of Us Research program’s 5 year goals to continue our collaborations and set the vision for future work plans.  

As the 2022 LULAC National Convention logistics are underway, we have had initial conversations of the execution to the event.  This includes potential areas of collaboration, outreach, and addressing attendees by All of Us representatives to create multiple touch points for the program. 

The LULAC team received an opportunity to table at the University of Texas at El Paso during a student conference on April 7-8 and was able to distribute general information regarding the program to student participants and answer questions regarding LULAC and the All of Us Health Research Program.
column59: Some of the challenges LULAC experienced during this month was finalizing a location for our Mental Health Cafecito initially scheduled for May. However, Rima Matsumoto has been helpful in putting us in contact with CASA de Maryland as a potential partner and site location.
column60: During the month of April, LULAC’s Health Programs Coordinator learned how to complete the CPGI Strategy Plan. When the Health Programs Coordinator was on boarded last year in June the CPGI Strategy Plan had already been completed, approved and ready to begin execution  activities Throughout LULAC’s conversations with Rima and throughout watching the workshops a message that resonated with us is that there needs to be multiple touch points to increasing participant recruitment and participation in the program. LULAC made it a priority to host multiple events within a market to increase visibility and awareness.
column61: LULAC had meetings with the All of Us team throughout the month of April to discuss the upcoming cafecito in May, social media communication updates and requests, and the CPGI Strategy Plan. Earlier this month LULAC met with Rima to discuss the CPGI Strategy Plan and get feedback on the plan. We also participated in the Chicago, NY and DMV market calls. LULAC received great feedback regarding the plan for the next cycle and began drafting responses to the questions raised by the review committee. Additionally, during our weekly check-in call Samantha Santoro shared communication updates regarding new toolkits uploaded to the asset portal. LULAC has incorporated social media posts regarding the researcher workbench into our communications plan. Additionally, we requested support from Samantha in drafting talking points and creating social media graphics for the Mental Health Awareness Month Cafecito that will take place in June, 2022 in the DMV. There will be two sessions for this cafecito event– one will be in Spanish and the other in English. LULAC shared this opportunity with other CPGI partners in the DMV market call and there has been expressed interest in collaborating on this event.

column2: AHECWW at Whatcom/ 2022 June Monthly Summary Report
column55: It was great to work with the VAP and to host a webinar with their trainers. Now we understand the process and were able to experience content from their general and researcher presentation kits.  AHECWW is trialing a new format to the WA AHEC Newsletter to see if it changes audience engagement with more pictures and dynamic design.  In May it did not work well with the AoU article in the middle of the newsletter.  We had improved click rates with positioning the article first, as one might expect.
column57: Burn-out/ exhaustion of health provider and student audience.  AHECWW needs to circle back to the conversation about participating in the journey project and potential to host at Community and Technical Colleges in WA.
column58: After 7 years of this program, what are the tangible results? Is there a resource/ webpage that highlights the connection from research done via the AoU of Research Workbench that is making a direct impact today in underserved communities?
column59: The AHECWW is still waiting for Whatcom Community College Marketing staff to be onboarded with capacity to assist us with our website and social media plan.  We were able to identify work arounds to move forward with website edits in the interim.  We scaled back our initial website and social media plan.  The landing page draft design was submitted for review by Samantha Santoro and then the full AoU CPGI program review process.  The AHECWW plans to first launch an Instagram account and then a Twitter Account with a Blog in the early part of the next fiscal year if successful in renewal of the grant.
column60: The AHECWW could still do more utilize resources on the All of Us Engagement Hub.  The AHECWW staff could spend more time in training and review of resources.
column61: The AHECWW has completed each task on the scope of work for 2021-2022.  The social media project did not include a full website with a robust social media presence. However, the center made significant progress despite a number of set backs during the first year of engagement on the project stemming from the pandemic and larger issues impacting academic settings and workforce.

column2: AAFP/April 2022 Monthly Report
column55:
1- Hosted All of Us Informational webinar on 4/12/22 with 123 registrants. Eighty-one people attended the webinar.
2- Fully executed DURA on 4/8/22
3 - AAFP staff members began Registering for Researcher accounts
4- Promotions tactics deployed this month included:
a. AAFP news story published on 4/5/22
b. Paid social media promotion through 4/11/22
c. Follow-up email to all registrants with instructions to register for a Researcher Account on 4/22/22
d. advertisement in a Family Practice Management Journal eNews email deployed on 3/30/22
5- Submitted initial plans for funding for 22-23 year program activities
6- Secured a date for the Deep Dive Discussion and working with Jakara to create agenda for event.
column57: We have not yet heard about barriers from our community members, but we are going to deploy a follow-up survey in May to find out more about experiences with the Research Hub.
column58:

We were unable to deploy our paid social media for the event until four days prior to the event. We plan to make a recording of the webinar available on our website and have been waiting for the video to be closed captioned.
column61: In early April, we were in frequent email communication with Rob about NIH website review. We also met with Rob and Jakara on 4/21 to discuss and plan for the deep dive discussion. Our team has met internally 3 times this month.

column2: Black Greek Letter Consortium/ Kappa Alpha Psi Summary April 2022
column55: For the period between the end of March 2022 and the Month of April 2022 we attended and participated in all BGLC calls and AOU monthly calls along with planning calls for Rooted in Resilience. We also held several calls preparing for our May 18th event titled “Avoid Suffering in Silence” which focused on mental health in the miliary.  We participated in the discussions around Rooted in Research as well as solicited potential sponsors for the program stops. We attended the Market Calls and gave input on different discussions being held. We worked with the core team on ordering needed items for the Atlanta stop as well as met with the local operations team to do a walkthrough of the venue selected for the Atlanta location event. Met with our team to discuss the 5-year plan along with giving input as to what our team would like to see. Held internal meetings with our leadership to discuss event ideas as we prepare for a mental health discussion with our Military and Veterans Commission. Held meetings with partner organizations to create a potential outreach program for the upcoming Summer Months. Also made several social media post in partnership with the other orgs on different posting strategies. Also presented information at the Southeastern Province Council and the other 11 Provinces as well. The presentations were mostly in person except for 2 that were virtual. Worked the events in Atlanta for Rooted in Resilience at Clark Atlanta University on April 22nd and the Community engagement event on April 23rd in East Point Commons. Aided in set up and break down along with soliciting vendors and artists for the overall event. Also assisted with the logistics of all events that were associated with the weekend and tour overall.
column59: The challenges that were presented were getting things done logistically with time and personnel. On Friday, April 22 due to timing and individual responsibilities we were at a shortage of manpower. Made a call to campus fraternity brothers and gained assistance for labor that was needed at the event. Assistance with putting things up along with loading and unloading.
column60: Marketing is extremely important with conducting events both virtually and in person. We have to make sure this is done efficiently and effectively. We can’t just leave this piece to Social Media as we have to establish a presence locally in the area to make sure the word is getting out about the events being done. We also have to think outside the box by potentially even transporting those that may not have the means to physically be present to get the word out.
column61: We attended all weekly meetings as well as the Local Atlanta NIH Meeting. We held briefing sessions to discuss our upcoming events as well as worked with our Social Media team to circulate All of Us information. We met with potential sponsors for the upcoming tour along with discussing potential ideas that may help with the Rooted in Resilience tour itself. Sent out various communication to our internal membership as well as our monthly newsletter on Health-related issues focusing as well on the program and the importance of clinical studies. Also encouraged our individual members to start to consider more people facing events by following the CDC guideline locally. Assisted with the Rooted and Resilience core planning by doing a site visit in Atlanta and walking the location. Ordered necessary needed items like the tent, tables, and chairs from one of the local vendors. Received assets from previous locations to store for the event along with assisting with the transport of the items to the events. column2: Black Greek Letter Consortium/  National Pan-Hellenic Council May Summary 2022
column55: Not that we have been confirmed for Phase VIII, we have been working on fining and tuning our plans for the scope of work. As previously discussed, we know that the focus is on research and retention. As such our idea to keep our table talk format will allow us some flexibility in engaging researchers and physicians that work with HPOs. We found that our format has been very successful as a virtual event, however, we are planning one hybrid event. The event will be broadcast live on Facebook and YouTube. We have identified several speakers for the upcoming events; we have had preliminary discussions with a large NPHC Council that is located in one of the market cities. We assisted with and/or participated in Sigma Gamma Rho's recent event.
column59: The collective BGLC organizations have each expressed concerns about the current expected delivery of the All of Us message during events. Several strategies are being reviewed to ensure that we honor the expectations of the program while creating strategies to keep our constituents engaged, with the presentation. Some of our ideas include making the NIH information more engaging so that the All of Us message flows through our activations seamlessly and connects with our participants. For example, we would incorporate the presentation about All of Us in a way that makes for a smoother transition with our content.
column60: As a result of participating in the CPGI Spring Engagement reviewing the CPGI Day Resources and Evaluation email, we gained greater insight into the trajectory of the All of Us program since Phase I. The growth and reach of the program are a direct result of all of the partnerships and the creative ideas for activations by the partners on all levels. We recognize that this program is ever-evolving and that our participation requires us to continue to evolve with the needs of the program. BGLC as a collective did a really good job of engaging our communities and enhancing awareness, but our work now will need to have a greater focus on research and retention. It is important to note that in Phase VI and Phase VII that we had begun moving in those directions with the development of the Rooted in Research and the Minority Student Research Symposium.
column61: This month we participated in all BGLC Meetings. We participated in our weekly planning meetings for NPHC. We participated in and supported events hosted by other BGLC organizations. We worked on our strategy document for phase VIII. We registered for and participated in the CPGI Spring Engagement. Although we could not stay for the entire meeting due to scheduling conflicts, we did review the CPGI Day Resources and Evaluation email, which gave us time to do a deeper dive into the statement of work document and the CPGI presentation.

column58:
Subawardess report insufficient assets, engageable content and graphics for engagement of new participants or rentention of LGBTQ participants. 

Specifically subawardees report:
Lack of a variety of content and visual assets to avoid repetition during each Cycle
Lack of diversity and imagery in available graphics
Lack of intersectional imagery within the LGBTQ subcommunities
Lack of content and assets for the research community relevant to LGBTQ communities
Lack of Pride assets available and updated year round, not all Pride events happen in June

Suggested :
Include queer graphic designers and artists, create more content that doesn’t include faces or people
Have subawardees submit detailed requests of who and what we want to see in new assets, disability communities included, as many details as we can imagine, representation of subcommunities within our communities, the current lack of diversity for some identities in current assets represented borderline tokenism

column2: Black Greek Letter Consortium/ Phi Beta Sigma Summary June 2022
column55:
Phi Beta Sigma Fraternity maintained both telecommunications and virtual meeting contact with the BGLC leadership team and the BGLC peer group throughout the thirty-day period of May 26, 2022 – June 25, 2022, by participating in weekly team calls and the bi-monthly social media All of Us team calls. 

Phi Beta Sigma Fraternity BGLC Assistant Coordinator Jarrod Benjamin participated as a Collaboration Partner in the New Orleans Regional Bank Chamber of Commerce Men's Health Week Facebook Live Event on Wednesday, June 15, 2022. The host was the New Orleans Regional Black Chamber of Commerce and the Southern University of New Orleans as well as the LSU Health Center (enrollment partner) that served on the initiative.  

During the month of June 2022, Phi Beta Sigma Fraternity coordinators worked to confirm the dates for activities in the cities designated for the phase of the All of Us research project.  The scheduled activities in Houston TX (on the campus of Huston-Tillotson University) will be in the month of October 2022. The scheduled activities in Itta Bena MS (on the campus of Mississippi Valley State University) will be in the month of October 2022.  

Phi Beta Sigma Fraternity coordinators worked to confirm the dates for activities that will provide community outreach and retention services for the Milwaukee WI area.  That activity will be a collaboration with Holy Redeemer Church of God in Christ, a minority faith-based organization.  The scheduled activities will be January 18 – 19, 2023.

Phi Beta Sigma Fraternity also changed its promotional pattern as an All of Us partner.  The information normally included in the social media platforms will now be placed in our weekly Programs Newsletter.  The newsletter has a reach of 30,000.

The goal is to get the participants to use the All of Us website to start the engagement and get questions answered.

column55: An accomplishment that we had this month was training our final student ambassador for this cycle that will be working with the program this summer.
column57: The greatest barrier to participation this month was for our AoU Student Ambassadors. Our student Ambassadors are currently at the end of the academic year which is a very heavy exam and finals time for students and faculty alike. this has made it more difficult for the Ambassadors to set up meeting times with faculty members to discuss AoU and how to get involved as a researcher. It has also been more difficult for Ambassadors to get into the classroom to talk with students and young researchers due to exams and limited class time.
column58: The greatest concern this month included communication with collaborators while planning for the National AHEC Organization All of Us Webinar.
column59: The most glaring challenge that we faced this month was with communication with Greensboro AHEC while we were planning the National AHEC Organization All of Us Webinar. We felt like there was a significant disconnect between what was discussed and the final product that was presented. In order to get to the best result, we made sure that we were overcommunicating through email and also being flexible to slight changes while also standing ground on topics that we thought should not be changed. We also had several meetings and run throughs. Following the event we also addressed this with our engagement counselor so she would know our concerns.
column60: A lesson learned this month was that best intentions don't always get the job done, but working towards a common goal and knowing when to pick your battles can be the best choice of action for getting to the end result.

column2: ACCESS Monthly Summary Report (April 2022)
column55:
ACCESS was able to draft an op-ed this month that highlighted the value of biodiverse data. With growing advances in Public Health Data Science, the All of Us Program enters at a time where health information is accelerating at a rapid rate. Big data, computing systems, and predictive analytics all utilize current health information and available profiles. Through the All of Us Program, the researcher consortium cultivates healthcare analytics that is heterogenous and reflective of our communities. We hope to develop this op-ed and remark on our impact on healthcare solutions to come. 

In addition to the op-ed, the students within the Public Health Society will be submitting an abstract. This abstract recaps their work in relation to the All of Us Program and the initiatives they have led on campus. We are proud of their work and we hope that this submission is recognized. We have also successfully met with new leadership and begun the transition process as the current student leaders are graduating. We hope to further connect with them via an upcoming picnic!
 
 We are also developing our scope of work for the upcoming months. We are currently strategizing new opportunities to re-engage the community around us and initiate recruitment efforts with the help of  Henry Ford Health.
column57:
There were very few barriers to participation this month. With steadfast efforts through social media posts and planning following events to come, goals were maintained. April also was the month of Ramadan, a period of fasting for many of the community members here. Members of all 3 collaborators observed Ramadan and strategized to host food-related events after its conclusion. Our community members spent the month focused on Ramadan, thus post-Ramadan is a season of renewed energy and joy. We hope to utilize this morale well in the upcoming month.
 As varying organizations transition and begin to assess a return to in-person events, we are also testing our comfort levels. There is interest and hope to bring our community members together, especially as warmer weather allows ease of gathering outside. We would like to be respectful of community members, and further build community amongst Access and our collaborators within the Metro-Detroit area. As Covid-19 begins to wane, we hope to reach our community members where they are.
column59: The Public Health Society has transitioned to new leadership, as current leaders are graduating from the University of Michigan Dearborn. With new leadership comes establishing relationships that understand the significance of the All of Us Program and how to navigate common goals. Access hopes that the success and willingness to collaborate with the Public Health Society at the University of Michigan Dearborn will continue to further programmatic recruitment and engage the student community here in Metro Detroit.
column60: Lessons learned include mindfulness when it comes to transitioning to the end of the pandemic. There is great enthusiasm to meet and engage with our fellow collaborators. Just as we practiced respectful social distancing throughout the entirety of the pandemic, we will continue to meet and host tabling events, community pop-ups, and other outreach plans respectfully. Access remains prepared to lead in-person initiatives, with intentions to only benefit community health.

Being able to use this consortium and identify similar events occurring around the nation helps realize the impact and reach of our combined efforts.

column2: ACCESS Monthly Summary Report (May 2022)
column55: Accomplishments for this month include further development of the op-ed shared with the All of Us Team. We are continuing to work on this op-ed and hope to share it with our communications team. We also had a picnic with our PHS leadership. This picnic was a segway to introduce us to the new team members we will be working with and it helped fostered trust within each other.
column57: There were few barriers to participation this month. Our efforts remained steadfast. We continued to collaborate with Henry Ford Health. There was an internal obstacle that occured when we attempted to plan our food series recordings. We triaged the situation accordingly and pushed our food series collaboration to July.
column58: Our concerns for May are key worries carried over from April. With growing interest to reintegrate in-person social events and communications, the pandemic continues to fluctuate. We will continue to remain respectful of the community surrounding us and navigate in-person events cautiously.
column59: There were few project challenges this month. As we have reached the end of our current funding cycle, we took this month to reflect upon what measures worked for ACCESS. We aim to start our upcoming funding cycle motivated and strengthened.
column60: Lessons learned included identifying what programmatic work is within ACCESS’s scope of work. As we conclude the funding cycle, we take time to assess what education, social media, and outreach efforts worked better than others. This information and growth is essential to allocating our time and resources as effectively as possible for the year to come. We hope to pinpoint areas of our community that can ensure program enrollment and participation for the year to come.

column2: Sci-Port Discovery Center/March Monthly Report
column55:
On 3/12/2022, Sci-Port Discovery Center hosted a Health Fair for the Northwestern State University School of Nursing.  A total of 569 people attended the Health Fair which resulted in approximately 12-15 quality engagements which involved the Pre- and Post Assessments.  I had received 1 hard copy of the surveys, which has been furnished to Pyxis.  The remaining surveys were taken on-line through a QR Code that was provided in the All of Us Exhibit.

The All of Us kiosk is continuing to receive attention at Sci-Port Discovery Center as evidenced by the interesting Post-It notes that visitors leave behind explaining why they think the program is important.  Photos are included herewith.
column57: The availability of the electronic technology including appropriate hardware to the populace in order to communicate with the All of Us webpage.
column58: The only common concern that we have come across is the availability of the internet and the appropriate hardware in order to access the All of Us website for the later steps for enrollment.
column59: There were several Webinars that were held earlier this month that I had registered for, but, due to other activities that came up, I was unable to attend them.  Specifically, the events were CPGI Workshops on 3/10, 3/11, 3/15 and 3/17.  If the workshops were recorded and made available, I could better honor my commitment to watch them.

I had received 1 hard copy of the surveys, which has been furnished to Pyxis.  The remaining surveys were taken on-line through a QR Code that was provided in the All of Us Exhibit.

The All of Us kiosk is continuing to receive attention at Sci-Port Discovery Center as evidenced by the interesting Post-It notes that visitors leave behind explaining why they think the program is important.  Photos are included herewith.
column156: There were several Webinars that were held earlier this month that I had registered for, but, due to other activities that came up, I was unable to attend them.  Specifically, the events were CPGI Workshops on 3/10, 3/11, 3/15 and 3/17.  If the workshops were recorded and made available, I could better honor my commitment to watch them.
column158: The availability of the electronic technology including appropriate hardware to the populace in order to communicate with the All of Us webpage.
column159: Although we are moving into an enlistment mode, there is still a great need to continue in an informative mode in our presentation of the basic All of Us message.  However, having said that, we are finding out that the All of Us message is getting out into the community as we have an increased number of people that we come across that are aware of the All of Us program.  More lately in conversations with individuals regarding All of Us, there appears to be a growing interest in the enrollment process.
column160: The only common concern that we have come across is the availability of the internet and the appropriate hardware in order to access the All of Us website for the later steps for enrollment.
