column59:
●	The SGRho Team is continuing their Health Stories series for the internal All of 
Us awareness campaign.  The series will continue through May when we launch our Mental Health series.
●	The amount of time it takes to have products reviewed can pose a challenge to event success if not received back in a timely fashion. Therefore, we worked hard to provide early and advanced notice of our May activities so that we could receive approvals in time for scheduled promotional activities.
●	Our team continues to meet regularly to fine-tune the plans within our Scope of Work and to address any service gaps in programming, while also looking for opportunities to share this information with wider audiences in the community at large.
column60: ●	Competing demands on the team’s time due to other responsibilities are weighing heavy. Constant communication as well as being able to quickly pivot will ensure the team’s success throughout the duration of the project.
column61:
●	Sigma Gamma Rho’s social media campaign has provided a consistent presence of promotion of the program on all of our social media channels.  As we continue to collect “health stories” from members of the organization, and also publicize All of Us on social media, we are anticipating an increase in followers and thereby reaching more people with our messages. We also began promoting our May Self Care Mental Health - All of Us webinar that will be coming up in May.
●	Our Atlanta team assisted with the Rooted in Resilience Tour this month, which helped to gain greater visibility in that market, as well as to strengthen community partnerships which we hope will lead to future events. Each tour stop includes three components: education with an HBCU, community, and faith partners. Details about the three events are available at www.rootedinresilience.com. The flyer for this month’s event is also attached.
●	We continue to brainstorm how to leverage the partnerships and resources we are learning about to the benefit of getting the word out about All of us, and we continue to fine-tune the plans within the Scope of Work to ensure ease and readiness of execution at the appropriate time.

column55: The CPGI Meeting was excellent.  It really helped to think through scope of work development and ways to improve outreach and demonstrate impact of work. column2: NHCOA Monthly Summary Report (July 2022)
column55: During this month, we worked on and finalized our Year 4 scope of work and budget. We engaged in significant meetings with our engagement counselor, Rima Matsumoto, to ensure partnerships and planning for the next phase aligned with program goals. Our scope of work and budget was approved, and we are working with our engagement counselor on a timeline of activities to be implemented in this new funding cycle. We also virtually met Mae Sandberg, our new engagement counselor, who will also work with us in our planned activities. Also, on July 20 we had a Zoom call with the Health Provider Organization (HPO) enrollment site from the California Market, to speak about possible collaboration opportunities for this new cycle. As part of our upcoming in person activities, on August 6 we will be participating in a health fair at Montgomery College in Maryland. In our calls with the engagement counselors, both have guided us to bring AoU giveaways and QR Codes that lead to the AoU regional DMV website, as well as bilingual educational flyers. We will partner with Mary's Center, who is helping us to enroll those who are interested in being part of the program. We also had a meeting with Samantha Santoro, Communications Counselor, who will be helping us in our communication plan. We continue to be active in our social media platforms by educating our community about the program.
column59: We experienced no challenges in this reporting period. We continue to meet bi-weekly with our engagement counselors to troubleshoot any issues as they arise.
column60: It has been great to start planning ahead of time for the upcoming All of Us Research program deliverables that we need to accomplish for this new funding cycle. Along with our engagement counselors Rima Matsumoto, Mae Sandberg, and Samantha Santoro, we are developing a timeline to keep track of the activities for this funding cycle. We are also securing speakers for virtual activities, including Cafecito con NHCOA (coffee time with NHCOA), knowing the All of Us Observance Calendar will supplement the activities that we have planned in our scope of work. We are continuing to utilize the social media toolkit.
column61: We are working in a sub-contract with the Diverse Elders Coalition (DEC) and are in talks to have a meeting to plan agreeable activities for this new funding cycle.

column2: NHCOA Monthly Summary Report (April 2022)
column55: During this month, we engaged in weekly meetings with our engagement counselor, Rima Matsumoto, to ensure partnerships and activities are aligned with program goals. We had a meeting with our engagement counselor to start with our strategic planning for the next funding cycle. As part of our in-person activities, on April 21, we did a bingo game with a focus on research, including the All of Us Research program, and nutrition at Casa Iris Housing Facility. We had over 20 participants who engaged in an interactive and educative session where they had the opportunity to learn about different health topics, tips to achieving good nutrition and physical health, and a recap in health research terminology and the importance of Hispanic/Latinos participating in health research and the All of Us Research program. Also, we are still finalizing logistics for the upcoming two webinars we are co-hosting with the DEC regarding perspectives from health researchers in advancing health equity in diverse communities scheduled for May 26 and June 23. We continue to be active on our social media platforms to educate and create awareness about the program and the importance of Hispanic/Latinos participating in health research.
column57: Due to the ongoing pandemic, we are conducting most of our events in a virtual setting. When we do conduct in-person events (e.g., bingo game) we make it a contactless experience. Meanwhile, we have been active on social media and doing virtual activities to promote the program and enrollment.

column2: NHCOA Monthly Summary Report
column55:
During this month, we engaged in weekly meetings with our engagement counselor, Rima Matsumoto, to ensure partnerships and activities are aligned with program goals. We had a meeting with our engagement counselor to discuss strategic planning for the next funding cycle.  On May 20, we developed and published the Cafecito con NHCOA with a focus on the future of the All of Us Research program. This Cafecito con NHCOA was conducted in Spanish and the video was widely disseminated through our social media platforms. Here’s the link to the video for more information: https://fb.watch/dlYPAZIV5k/  . We also worked with the communications team to help us promote the Cafecito con NHCOA videos via our social media platforms.

Also, we had a planning call with the communications team and engagement counselor to discuss promotional materials for the webinar scheduled on May 26th. As part of our virtual activities, we co-hosted the Perspectives from Health Researchers in Advancing Health Equity in Diverse Communities: Part 1” webinar alongside the Diverse Elders Coalition (DEC).

We had over 100 attendees who joined the discussion with a panel of experts to learn about persisting health inequities and barriers that have prevented communities of color, LGBTQ+ communities, American Indian/Alaska Native communities, and others from participating in health research and how the All of Us Research Program aims to resolve these inequities, making it easier for diverse communities to participate in health research. Also, we are finalizing logistics for the second part of the Perspectives from Health Researchers in Advancing Health Equity in Diverse Communities webinar that we are co-hosting with the DEC and is scheduled to take place on June 23rd.  We continue to be active on our social media platforms to educate and create awareness about the program and the importance of Hispanic/Latinos participating in health research.

column2: NHCOA Monthly Summary Report (June 2022)
column55: It has been great to start planning ahead of time for the upcoming All of Us Research Program deliverables that we need to accomplish for this new funding cycle. Along with our engagement counselor and the communications team, we are keeping track of the timeline related to the activities for this funding cycle. One of the lessons learned during this month was the importance of sharing the promotional materials (ex. flyers and the RSVP link and that the communications team help us develop) for our webinar among the Miami, DMV and NY market to better promote our event, along with sharing it in the CPGI digest e-newsletter.
column57: Due to the ongoing pandemic, we are conducting most of our events in a virtual setting. When we do conduct in-person events (e.g., bingo games and mini health fairs) we make it a contactless experience. Meanwhile, we have been active on social media and doing virtual activities to promote the program and enrollment.
column59: We experienced no challenges in this reporting period. We continue to meet weekly with our CPGI engagement counselor to troubleshoot any issues as they arise.
column60: During this month, we engaged in weekly meetings with our engagement counselor, Rima Matsumoto, to ensure partnerships and activities are aligned with program goals. We continue to meet with our engagement counselor to discuss strategic planning for the next funding cycle.  Also, we had a planning call with the communications team and engagement counselor to discuss promotional materials for the webinar scheduled on June 23. As part of our virtual activities,  we co-hosted the “Perspectives from Health Researchers in Advancing Health Equity in Diverse Communities: Part 2” webinar along with the Diverse Elders Coalition (DEC). Also, we collaborated with organizations from the DMV area to conduct an in person health fair titled as “United for our Health” in Hyattsville, Maryland on June 25.  During this health fair, NHCOA served as a moderator for the Cafecito con LULAC and we incorporated 10 older adults into this activity. During the Cafecito, seniors were able to learn more about mental health among Hispanics/Latinos, know more about mental health resources available to the community, and about the All of Us Research program and how the program is helping researchers understand why people get sick or stay healthy. We continue to be active on our social media platforms to educate and create awareness about the program and the importance of Hispanic/Latinos participating in health research.

column2: Xavier University- May 2022 Monthly Report
column55: Dr. Lemieux was invited to be a guest panelist on the "Researcher Engagement" session on day two of the Spring Engagement conference on 5/5/22. On 5/27/22 Dr. Lemieux was asked to give a presentation on the All of Us Research Program to the RCMI/NIH's Program Officer who was interested in learning more about the program.
column59:
We had a couple of challenges this month. We would like to note that HPO partner Tulane sent an email to meet following our in-person Louisiana Ecosystem meeting in late March. A meeting was planned and scheduled for May 9th by Nicole Blunt. This meeting was initiated by Marie (Engagement coordinator) who invited Blair (Project Manager) & Emily (leaving program soon) to attend from Tulane. Tulane entered the meeting with their cameras off and was clearly unprepared for discussion. Dr. Lemieux begin by asking questions about how we could collaborate and what was Tulane currently doing in the community. We discovered Tulane had no engagement strategy and that the current team is unempathetic and displayed micro-aggressions when asked questions regarding current and past engagement strategies and experiences with the community. It gave us grave concerns around their ability to connect with community and we are very protective of the community we serve. Dr. Lemieux suggested that once they have a community engagement plan we can reconvene for further discussion. 
The second challenge was around Xavier's upcoming AoU Workbench & R training. After Dr. Watson mention Xavier's training at the Spring Engagement and Dr. Lemieux shared during our Ecosystem meeting our future events, we received a considerable amount of interest from NIH staff, DREF and others in the All of Us Constrosium. While we welcome the spirit of collaboration, Xavier's funding is limited to community engagement. We are committed to expanding our cohort of UBR researcher in the HBCU commuity per our SOW and welcome the support and resources to serve more in the next round of funding as a sub-awardee of Pyxis Partners.

column2: Xavier University- April 2022 Monthly Report
column55:
Dr. Lemieux was a guest speaker in a seminar series with the Louisiana Cancer Research Center in partnership with Xavier's Center for Minority Health & Health Disparities. The title of her presentation was "An Introduction to XULA HEALS in the CommUNITY." The presentation introduced faculty to the AoURP and the AoU Workbench and Research Hub. 
Dr. Lemieux & Nicole met with the Center for Minority Health & Health Disparitie's Community Advisor Board LA-SEAL to introduce the All of Us Research Program and to put out "feelers" to see if they would be interested in a collaboration to promote community engagement and enrollment. This initial meeting was promising and we are looking forward to developing an organic relationship with the CAB. We also meet with faculty across multiple disciplines to discuss board curriculum integration and researcher tooling in regards to the AoURP and Workbench/Data Browser. The response was overwhelming positive and faculty are working with their respective departments to secure approval to participate.
column57: CAB members expressed  possible concerns about community members having access to transportation and limitations with smart devices for enrollment.
column58: During our discussion with the LA-CEAL CAB, board members were receptive to our invitation to have a "live" experience of their own to share with community members who may consider engaging and possibly enrolling in the AoURP as a way to facilitate trust in the enrollment process. The concern expressed was one of being authentic about engaging the community without appearing out of touch with the community.
column59: We had minimal challenges this month. column2: AAFP/ June 2022 Monthly Report
column55:
Hosted Deep Dive Discussion with 12 participants on 6/6/22.
Interviewed an additional participant on 6/15/22. This person viewed the recorded Deep Dive Discussion and Angie Lanigan asked the agreed upon questions.
Recruited a physician to draft a testimonial about their experience with the All of Us program.
Representatives from team attended All of Us CPGI meetings on 6/14/22.
column57:
There are physicians interested in registering for Research Hub accounts that are not affiliated with a university or academic medical centers. There is a desire to expand access or create some way to match people with mentors or researchers with access to ask questions

Participants expressed concerns that they may need support with the Hub after they have an account. Would like information about reaching out if they have questions within the Research Hub. Consider advertising the office hours prominently on the website.

Some physicians who attended Deep Dive have flyers in their clinics to recruit participants to All of Us, but they have no idea how many of their patients actually register and sign up. Mentioned that it is difficult in the course of a busy clinic day/short office visit to have in-depth conversations with patients about the program.
column58:
Concerns/questions discussed during the deep dive included:
-What type of file is genetic data? Can researchers have access to raw data?
-How much is the incentive payment to participants for survey completion?
-Can the All of Us platform be used to advertise study opportunities to All of Us participants (ex: Alzheimer's or dementia)?
-Are there plans to have surveys translated in other languages?
-Are there any planned collaborations with organizations that have their own registries (ex: Kaiser)?
-Concern that only having All of Us research participant surveys online will create an inherent bias in the data.
-People are interested in potentially using All of Us to triangulate or verify data from other sources for surveillance or health care utilization studies.
column59: We have not experienced any challenges this month.
column60:
Physicians and researchers interested in health disparity research are excited about the Research Hub.

Physicians in teaching roles are excited to use All of Us data to teach medical students/residents about research.

column16: New Orleans Regional Black Chamber of Commerce
column55:
In celebration of Men's Health Month, NORBCC along with our Regional Collaboration Partners hosted a Men's Health Week event surrounding the importance of health and wellness for men in business and our community. We leveraged social media platforms to prompt discussions leading into a Facebook Live event with featured specialists on Wednesday, June 15th.   

Panelists were able to engage with approximately 15 attendees for an in depth discussion about preventive messures men can focus on to ensure they are making their health a priority, to ultimately more effectively manage their operations. Attendees were exposed to opportunities in which All of Us research can help in achieving their wellness goals.
column57: Lack of relatable community figures who have completed enrollment in programs and share their experiences.
column58: Overall community tone shows interest in learning more about available opportunities, but there is hesitation in being unable to directly connect program's benefits with community members they identify with.  Data privacy and trust continue to be a concern
column59: We have opportunties in our engagement processes. With this being a virtual event, we need to review areas in which we can more heavily promote the significance of our All of Us content to better engage attendees and channel them into being more active
column60:
We've identified that there is strong community curiosity in the potential advantages of participation. We now look to create a campaign that features community figures and leaders to encourage enrollment and highlight benefits. 

We have connected with our LSU enrollment partner to develop a series of events that provide more details in programming and enrollment for our community.

Gerry Infante did an "EXTRA" event in Detroit (5th event for the year) withpartner up with Henry Ford HPO. This was an in-person event: 5 de Mayo Fiesta and Parade in Detroit. NAHN-Michigan partnered with the “Mexican Patriotic Committee of Metro Detroit” to provide a First Aid booth for the event participants for the Cinco de Mayo Fiesta and Parade. 

As well, DC Metro Chapter had two speakers (Izzy and Erika) as part of the 4/05 filming for the provider training module. Erika Ventura Castellon and Isolina Pistolizi participated in a community education with a panel of speakers: Conversations with the Community: A Provider Training Module.

column63:
17th year of their event, speakers, flowers, very professional, lunch served, 450 there, 300 online -- Greetings.
On behalf of the APU Research Symposium Team - thank you for all of your contributions to our Symposium events and success. 
Wednesday night's presentation informed us of the research opportunities with the existing "All of Us" data.
Thursday's presentation was very educational for our students, faculty, and community members; and aligned with our theme of health equity.
Of course, dinner and stories provided us with fun and a very pleasant opportunity to get to know you and your fascinating story. It was great to find out you were already part of the APU community - a blast from your past!
I don't want to forget to mention Molly's role in keeping all the details together for our grant and coordination efforts.
With gratitude,
Teresa and all of our APU Team   - come back and visit us again :)

column60:
When targeting the male population, we must include women because as stated by the two medical male presenters, women sometimes must take the lead in men’s healthcare. 
Minority men are still questioning “research” after the Tuskegee syphilis study. 
Nursing is a predominantly female profession We should promote our male counterparts and meet men where they are; barbershops, sports activities social events, etc. The men did say that they would be more open to males in “their spaces” than females.  Also, we are just relaxing the mask mandates in New Orleans post COVID OMICRON peak. We are slowly getting back to our “new normal”.  This was the first in person event we have offered in almost two years. The participants said it was great getting out to learn and interact for such a great purpose.
column62: The interest that the men had in health care questions and their willingness to discuss general healthcare questions with the providers. The male medical presenters offered some time for “private” conversations and the men took advantage of the opportunity. Some of them even said that they were going to follow up with primary providers and begin to engage preventive health care.

We also discussed the need to educate female so that they know what to expect when they seek healthcare and the questions to ask. participants also touched on the obvious discrimination and lack of equality in health care, i.e., cardiovascular care and maternal health care.  Some of the women shared personal stories and experiences of their family members. 

Now that we know more about COVID-19 and vaccinations are available we need to meet the community where they are and resume offering health education events in neighborhoods, i.e., community centers, parks, etc.

column2: AAFP/AoU Research Hub Deep Dive Discussion
column52: Physicians and researchers interested in health disparity research are excited about the Research Hub. Physicians in teaching roles are excited to use All of Us data to teach medical students/residents about research.
column56: Concerns/questions discussed during the deep dive included: -What type of file is genetic data? Can researchers have access to raw data? -How much is the incentive payment to participants for survey completion? -Can the All of Us platform be used to advertise study opportunities to All of Us participants (ex: Alzheimer's or dementia)? -Are there plans to have surveys translated in other languages? -Are there any planned collaborations with organizations that have their own registries (ex: Kaiser)? -Concern that only having All of Us research participant surveys online will create an inherent bias in the data. -People are interested in potentially using All of Us to triangulate or verify data from other sources for surveillance or health care utilization studies.

column2: BGLC: Phi Beta Sigma June Summary 2020
column107:
Phi Beta Signa Fraternity maintained contact with the BGLC Lead Jennifer Jones and the BGLC peer group by participating in weekly calls and preparing for the All of Us training that was offered March 16 â April 15, 2020.  Recent fraternity activities focused on preparation for the virtual face-to-face meeting sponsored by the All of Us Research Team.  The program coordination team continued to make attempts to provide service for a âtargetâ population, Houston TX.  The local area Brothers assisted in working with a local university (Texas Southern University) for the showing of the Henrietta Lack movie via a teleconference streaming service. 

When it became apparent that none of those planned activations in Houston TX would be possible, Phi Beta Sigma Fraternity worked to provide an internal training for over 1,600 new members of the organization that have been initiated from September 2019 â March 2020.  This would be made possible via a teleconference streaming service.  Tentative date of execution is during the last week of May 2020.
Program Coordinator Anderson participated in the training offered by BGLC Lead Jennifer Jones to NPHC Executive Directors for the upcoming Rooted in Research webinar series.  He obtained an agreement of participation from the International President of Phi Beta Sigma Fraternity, Micheal E. Cristal.  He also an agreement of participation from the New Jersey Commissioner of Education, Bro. Dr. Lamont Repollet, as a participant in the webinar series.
column108: Due to restrictions being applied to group activities larger than 10 attendees, the Phi Beta Sigma Fraternity team was notified that all of its planned activations and group activities had been postponed.  The team will maintain contact with the local connections and school officials.
column109: The primary lesson learned from these circumstances is that Phi Beta Sigma Fraternity should always have a secondary plan when it comes to coordinating activations.  We do not control site, weather or health conditions.
column111: Phi Beta Sigma Fraternity continues to execute plans to stage a virtual activation in Houston TX, a target market city for the All of Us project.  We will work to promote the Rooted in Research webinar series and we have accepted the topic of Education as our content specialty.  We are seeking to stay connected with the All of Us research project by participating in the upcoming virtual face-to-face meeting.
